WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.960 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:01.960 --> 00:00:03.920 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:03.920 --> 00:00:06.370 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:06.370 --> 00:00:11.100 align:middle line:90%


00:00:11.100 --> 00:00:16.640 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING: OK, so assume
that again that we have--

00:00:16.640 --> 00:00:17.810 align:middle line:90%
so this is a sequence.

00:00:17.810 --> 00:00:21.760 align:middle line:90%


00:00:21.760 --> 00:00:26.700 align:middle line:84%
Then from a sequence, we
can form another sequence.

00:00:26.700 --> 00:00:46.280 align:middle line:84%
So from a-n we can form
another sequence, at least.

00:00:46.280 --> 00:00:49.490 align:middle line:90%
If a-n is bounded from above.

00:00:49.490 --> 00:00:58.080 align:middle line:90%


00:00:58.080 --> 00:01:03.530 align:middle line:84%
So we can form another sequence,
and that's what we take.

00:01:03.530 --> 00:01:12.150 align:middle line:84%
B-n is going to be the soup of
the set of a, starting at n.

00:01:12.150 --> 00:01:16.946 align:middle line:90%


00:01:16.946 --> 00:01:21.400 align:middle line:84%
So this here is the
sequence b-n, OK?

00:01:21.400 --> 00:01:24.036 align:middle line:90%


00:01:24.036 --> 00:01:27.110 align:middle line:84%
But again, implicitly
here we are assuming.

00:01:27.110 --> 00:01:46.570 align:middle line:84%
So assume that there exists
some c, so that for all n a-n

00:01:46.570 --> 00:01:47.470 align:middle line:90%
is less than c.

00:01:47.470 --> 00:01:51.250 align:middle line:84%
In other words, the c are
bounded from above, right?

00:01:51.250 --> 00:01:56.290 align:middle line:84%
So if the sequence a-n
is bounded from above,

00:01:56.290 --> 00:02:02.430 align:middle line:84%
then this here gives
us a real number,

00:02:02.430 --> 00:02:11.190 align:middle line:84%
and we see that if you're
looking at b-n plus 1,

00:02:11.190 --> 00:02:20.590 align:middle line:84%
this is now sup of a-n
plus 1, a-n plus 2.

00:02:20.590 --> 00:02:25.750 align:middle line:84%
And this here is sup
over a smaller set,

00:02:25.750 --> 00:02:31.750 align:middle line:84%
so this is less
than the sup where

00:02:31.750 --> 00:02:33.500 align:middle line:90%
we take sup over a larger set.

00:02:33.500 --> 00:02:36.230 align:middle line:90%


00:02:36.230 --> 00:02:37.860 align:middle line:90%
And that here is b-n.

00:02:37.860 --> 00:02:40.830 align:middle line:90%


00:02:40.830 --> 00:02:45.410 align:middle line:84%
So we have that if
you take any sequence,

00:02:45.410 --> 00:02:48.610 align:middle line:84%
and let's say that that
sequence is bounded from above,

00:02:48.610 --> 00:02:52.950 align:middle line:84%
then you can form
another sequence b-n,

00:02:52.950 --> 00:02:56.740 align:middle line:84%
and b-n here is
monotone decreasing.

00:02:56.740 --> 00:03:05.160 align:middle line:90%


00:03:05.160 --> 00:03:22.400 align:middle line:84%
If the sequence b-n
is bounded from below,

00:03:22.400 --> 00:03:25.040 align:middle line:84%
then the b-n here
in the sequence

00:03:25.040 --> 00:03:30.680 align:middle line:84%
here converge, and it converges
to the infimum, right?

00:03:30.680 --> 00:03:34.160 align:middle line:84%
This is this with
monotone converging.

00:03:34.160 --> 00:03:37.640 align:middle line:84%
Sequences, it's
converging to the infimum

00:03:37.640 --> 00:03:44.050 align:middle line:90%
of the b-n like that.

00:03:44.050 --> 00:03:44.550 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:03:44.550 --> 00:03:55.460 align:middle line:90%


00:03:55.460 --> 00:03:58.060 align:middle line:84%
So likewise, although
we won't really

00:03:58.060 --> 00:04:07.920 align:middle line:84%
use this here, but
likewise, again,

00:04:07.920 --> 00:04:13.380 align:middle line:84%
if a-n is any
sequence, any sequence,

00:04:13.380 --> 00:04:15.910 align:middle line:84%
this time I want it to
be bounded from below.

00:04:15.910 --> 00:04:22.700 align:middle line:90%


00:04:22.700 --> 00:04:25.540 align:middle line:90%
Then you can find a sequence.

00:04:25.540 --> 00:04:31.140 align:middle line:84%
From a-n, you can form
a sequence, c-n, and c-n

00:04:31.140 --> 00:04:35.210 align:middle line:84%
is just where you're taking
the infimum, starting at a-n.

00:04:35.210 --> 00:04:40.240 align:middle line:90%


00:04:40.240 --> 00:04:44.980 align:middle line:84%
And you see that if you're
looking at c-n plus 1, then

00:04:44.980 --> 00:04:48.310 align:middle line:84%
you take the infimum
over a smaller set.

00:04:48.310 --> 00:04:55.750 align:middle line:90%


00:04:55.750 --> 00:04:58.630 align:middle line:90%
So this is a smaller set.

00:04:58.630 --> 00:05:04.550 align:middle line:84%
And so this here is bigger than
where you're taking the infimum

00:05:04.550 --> 00:05:11.710 align:middle line:90%
from a-n, and that's c-n.

00:05:11.710 --> 00:05:17.550 align:middle line:84%
So the sequence c-n is
therefore monotone increasing.

00:05:17.550 --> 00:05:19.690 align:middle line:90%
And if it is bounded--

00:05:19.690 --> 00:05:38.710 align:middle line:84%
so if c-n Is bounded from above,
then the sequence c-n converge

00:05:38.710 --> 00:05:48.230 align:middle line:84%
to some c, and that c is
just a sup of the c;s, right?

00:05:48.230 --> 00:05:55.490 align:middle line:84%
And we talked a little
bit about this earlier,

00:05:55.490 --> 00:05:59.650 align:middle line:84%
but now we will use
it in just a second.

00:05:59.650 --> 00:06:04.490 align:middle line:84%
The thing is, though, that
in the first case here,

00:06:04.490 --> 00:06:13.340 align:middle line:84%
we call b here, B is written
as the limsup of the a-n.

00:06:13.340 --> 00:06:15.850 align:middle line:90%


00:06:15.850 --> 00:06:25.580 align:middle line:84%
And in the second case, it's
called the liminf of the a-n.

00:06:25.580 --> 00:06:26.080 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:06:26.080 --> 00:06:33.010 align:middle line:90%


00:06:33.010 --> 00:06:35.610 align:middle line:84%
So why is this
relevant here for us?

00:06:35.610 --> 00:06:40.170 align:middle line:84%
So what we were
looking at last time--

00:06:40.170 --> 00:06:43.050 align:middle line:84%
and I'm only going
to use the limsup.

00:06:43.050 --> 00:06:46.630 align:middle line:90%
So last time, we had a sequence.

00:06:46.630 --> 00:06:57.060 align:middle line:84%
So a-n was a sequence,
and we defined

00:06:57.060 --> 00:06:59.500 align:middle line:90%
what we call a power series.

00:06:59.500 --> 00:07:02.860 align:middle line:84%
And again, power
series, think about that

00:07:02.860 --> 00:07:06.260 align:middle line:84%
x as being just
some fixed number,

00:07:06.260 --> 00:07:07.900 align:middle line:90%
and you have the sequence a-n.

00:07:07.900 --> 00:07:14.740 align:middle line:84%
X is some fixed number, and then
you form the sequence a-n x-n,

00:07:14.740 --> 00:07:16.980 align:middle line:90%
right?

00:07:16.980 --> 00:07:23.180 align:middle line:84%
And so for each x fixed,
this gives you some number.

00:07:23.180 --> 00:07:24.860 align:middle line:90%
Maybe, if it's converged.

00:07:24.860 --> 00:07:26.360 align:middle line:90%
I mean, you can ask for each x.

00:07:26.360 --> 00:07:29.420 align:middle line:84%
You can ask, does this
sequence converge or not?

00:07:29.420 --> 00:07:32.260 align:middle line:84%
And this here is
called a power series.

00:07:32.260 --> 00:07:34.760 align:middle line:84%
So you're summing
from 0 to whatever.

00:07:34.760 --> 00:07:36.900 align:middle line:84%
Or you're starting from
one, or whatever you're

00:07:36.900 --> 00:07:38.840 align:middle line:90%
starting with up to infinity.

00:07:38.840 --> 00:07:41.700 align:middle line:90%
So this is a power series.

00:07:41.700 --> 00:07:48.840 align:middle line:84%
And so now for power
series, the question

00:07:48.840 --> 00:07:54.880 align:middle line:84%
is, how serious is
the question is,

00:07:54.880 --> 00:08:01.510 align:middle line:84%
for which, for which
x does it converge?

00:08:01.510 --> 00:08:08.520 align:middle line:90%


00:08:08.520 --> 00:08:10.800 align:middle line:84%
So that's what we're
interested in,.

00:08:10.800 --> 00:08:13.963 align:middle line:90%


00:08:13.963 --> 00:08:15.880 align:middle line:84%
So just let me remind
you, because we're going

00:08:15.880 --> 00:08:18.580 align:middle line:90%
to use that anyway in a minute.

00:08:18.580 --> 00:08:24.280 align:middle line:90%
So example from last time.

00:08:24.280 --> 00:08:29.760 align:middle line:90%


00:08:29.760 --> 00:08:34.600 align:middle line:84%
The example we looked at last
time was we're looking at x-n.

00:08:34.600 --> 00:08:36.840 align:middle line:84%
And we looked at some
other examples, too,

00:08:36.840 --> 00:08:39.880 align:middle line:84%
but this was the one
we're focused on.

00:08:39.880 --> 00:08:42.020 align:middle line:90%
So this here is a power series.

00:08:42.020 --> 00:08:47.750 align:middle line:84%
The a-n in this case here
are 1 over n factorial.

00:08:47.750 --> 00:08:53.810 align:middle line:90%


00:08:53.810 --> 00:09:00.250 align:middle line:84%
And for each fixed
x, so for x fixed

00:09:00.250 --> 00:09:03.770 align:middle line:84%
we looked at whether or not
this sequence converges.

00:09:03.770 --> 00:09:07.730 align:middle line:84%
And so we think about
this thing here.

00:09:07.730 --> 00:09:08.950 align:middle line:90%
We thought this here.

00:09:08.950 --> 00:09:11.410 align:middle line:84%
We thought about it
as just a sequence

00:09:11.410 --> 00:09:16.270 align:middle line:90%
like this, sum of a sequence.

00:09:16.270 --> 00:09:21.890 align:middle line:84%
So this is as a series like
this, where the d-n here is now

00:09:21.890 --> 00:09:24.790 align:middle line:90%
x to the n over n factorial.

00:09:24.790 --> 00:09:27.360 align:middle line:90%


00:09:27.360 --> 00:09:32.290 align:middle line:84%
And so in order to determine for
which x it converges-- so just

00:09:32.290 --> 00:09:33.870 align:middle line:90%
think about x as being fixed.

00:09:33.870 --> 00:09:35.300 align:middle line:90%
We use the ratio test.

00:09:35.300 --> 00:09:41.290 align:middle line:90%


00:09:41.290 --> 00:09:46.670 align:middle line:84%
So we use the ratio
test, and the ratio test

00:09:46.670 --> 00:09:52.270 align:middle line:84%
said that if you're looking
at d-n plus 1 over d-n,

00:09:52.270 --> 00:09:58.470 align:middle line:84%
this here is where d-n is
just x to the n plus 1,

00:09:58.470 --> 00:10:07.430 align:middle line:84%
over n plus 1 factorial, divided
by x to the n over n factorial.

00:10:07.430 --> 00:10:09.350 align:middle line:90%
And that's the same.

00:10:09.350 --> 00:10:13.290 align:middle line:84%
So when you divide by a
fraction, you just switch.

00:10:13.290 --> 00:10:17.230 align:middle line:84%
So this is the same as x
to the n plus 1, divided

00:10:17.230 --> 00:10:25.310 align:middle line:84%
by n plus 1 factorial, times
n factorial, times x to the n.

00:10:25.310 --> 00:10:27.710 align:middle line:84%
And you just think
about this, the top

00:10:27.710 --> 00:10:32.710 align:middle line:84%
here, as x to the n times
x, times n factorial.

00:10:32.710 --> 00:10:37.110 align:middle line:84%
And the denominator you think
about as n plus 1 times n

00:10:37.110 --> 00:10:39.310 align:middle line:90%
factorial, times x to the n.

00:10:39.310 --> 00:10:44.070 align:middle line:84%
And you see that this here and
this here cancel with those two.

00:10:44.070 --> 00:10:50.160 align:middle line:90%
And so you get x over n plus 1.

00:10:50.160 --> 00:10:55.920 align:middle line:84%
And this here converges to 0,
so therefore the power series

00:10:55.920 --> 00:10:58.160 align:middle line:90%
is convergent for all x.

00:10:58.160 --> 00:11:00.780 align:middle line:90%


00:11:00.780 --> 00:11:06.400 align:middle line:84%
So that was a particular
example of a power series,

00:11:06.400 --> 00:11:11.720 align:middle line:84%
and it worked well
with the ratio test.

00:11:11.720 --> 00:11:13.980 align:middle line:84%
But the word test
actually is better.

00:11:13.980 --> 00:11:18.940 align:middle line:84%
And this was related to a point
somebody raised last time.

00:11:18.940 --> 00:11:23.740 align:middle line:84%
And that point was
for the ratio test,

00:11:23.740 --> 00:11:28.280 align:middle line:84%
it was implicitly somehow in
the ratio test, was something

00:11:28.280 --> 00:11:32.160 align:middle line:84%
about that from some
stage on, the next element

00:11:32.160 --> 00:11:34.380 align:middle line:84%
is smaller than
the previous one.

00:11:34.380 --> 00:11:38.520 align:middle line:84%
And you don't really
need to have that.

00:11:38.520 --> 00:11:43.440 align:middle line:84%
I mean, you certainly don't need
it for a series to converge,

00:11:43.440 --> 00:11:49.260 align:middle line:84%
but it's not even necessary
if you apply the right test.

00:11:49.260 --> 00:11:56.100 align:middle line:84%
And so this brings
us to what's called

00:11:56.100 --> 00:12:00.460 align:middle line:90%
the radius of convergence.

00:12:00.460 --> 00:12:08.620 align:middle line:84%
So this is a crucial concept,
and by this crucial concept,

00:12:08.620 --> 00:12:12.140 align:middle line:84%
because you see a priori
what you could imagine--

00:12:12.140 --> 00:12:18.200 align:middle line:84%
so suppose you just write
down a power series like this.

00:12:18.200 --> 00:12:22.180 align:middle line:90%


00:12:22.180 --> 00:12:28.060 align:middle line:84%
Maybe it's convergent
for when x is equal to 5,

00:12:28.060 --> 00:12:30.980 align:middle line:84%
it's divergent when
x is equal to 10,

00:12:30.980 --> 00:12:35.440 align:middle line:84%
and maybe it's converging
again if x is equal to 20.

00:12:35.440 --> 00:12:38.500 align:middle line:84%
That's not actually
going to be the case.

00:12:38.500 --> 00:12:41.320 align:middle line:84%
So there's something called
radius of convergence.

00:12:41.320 --> 00:12:50.990 align:middle line:90%


00:12:50.990 --> 00:12:53.190 align:middle line:84%
And the thing is
that what you get out

00:12:53.190 --> 00:12:57.750 align:middle line:84%
of this radius of convergence
is that a power series like this

00:12:57.750 --> 00:13:02.830 align:middle line:84%
is convergent on some interval,
and then outside this interval

00:13:02.830 --> 00:13:04.670 align:middle line:90%
is divergent.

00:13:04.670 --> 00:13:08.950 align:middle line:84%
So it's not like you have
some that is convergent here,

00:13:08.950 --> 00:13:12.550 align:middle line:84%
it's divergent there, and
then it's converging again.

00:13:12.550 --> 00:13:14.090 align:middle line:84%
That's not what's
going to happen.

00:13:14.090 --> 00:13:16.590 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:13:16.590 --> 00:13:20.990 align:middle line:84%
Part of this we already
saw in the different tests

00:13:20.990 --> 00:13:27.830 align:middle line:84%
that at the boundary
of this interval,

00:13:27.830 --> 00:13:29.750 align:middle line:84%
the test is
inconclusive, so you have

00:13:29.750 --> 00:13:33.950 align:middle line:84%
to check the
boundaries separately.

00:13:33.950 --> 00:13:38.790 align:middle line:84%
And so the idea is
that you check--

00:13:38.790 --> 00:13:45.370 align:middle line:84%
so you have a power
series like this,

00:13:45.370 --> 00:13:48.810 align:middle line:84%
and you think about-- again,
you're thinking about d-n

00:13:48.810 --> 00:13:51.022 align:middle line:90%
as x to the n.

00:13:51.022 --> 00:13:54.490 align:middle line:84%
X, again, is thought
of being fixed,

00:13:54.490 --> 00:13:56.750 align:middle line:90%
and now you apply the root test.

00:13:56.750 --> 00:13:58.530 align:middle line:84%
So apply the root
test, but I'm going

00:13:58.530 --> 00:14:03.000 align:middle line:84%
to apply it in a better form
than what we did last time.

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:07.050 align:middle line:90%


00:14:07.050 --> 00:14:10.300 align:middle line:84%
Maybe I'll just state first the
better form of the root test.

00:14:10.300 --> 00:14:16.970 align:middle line:90%


00:14:16.970 --> 00:14:21.530 align:middle line:84%
Here's the real version
of the root test.

00:14:21.530 --> 00:14:25.050 align:middle line:90%
So suppose you take a series.

00:14:25.050 --> 00:14:26.990 align:middle line:84%
Suppose you have
some series here.

00:14:26.990 --> 00:14:30.364 align:middle line:90%


00:14:30.364 --> 00:14:34.330 align:middle line:90%
Let's just call it d.

00:14:34.330 --> 00:14:36.040 align:middle line:84%
Suppose you take a
series like this.

00:14:36.040 --> 00:14:41.900 align:middle line:90%


00:14:41.900 --> 00:14:45.900 align:middle line:84%
So now the root test,
you took d-n, you

00:14:45.900 --> 00:14:49.270 align:middle line:84%
took the absolute value,
and you took the n-th root.

00:14:49.270 --> 00:14:52.440 align:middle line:90%


00:14:52.440 --> 00:14:55.500 align:middle line:84%
When I looked at the
root test last time,

00:14:55.500 --> 00:14:59.700 align:middle line:84%
we looked at whether this
is convergent or not.

00:14:59.700 --> 00:15:03.010 align:middle line:84%
So we said if it was
converging to something, right?

00:15:03.010 --> 00:15:06.740 align:middle line:84%
but you could form
this thing here.

00:15:06.740 --> 00:15:09.480 align:middle line:84%
So you could form
from this here.

00:15:09.480 --> 00:15:10.520 align:middle line:90%
You could form this.

00:15:10.520 --> 00:15:14.560 align:middle line:84%
This is now a sequence, and you
could look at limsup of this.

00:15:14.560 --> 00:15:18.980 align:middle line:90%


00:15:18.980 --> 00:15:25.340 align:middle line:84%
These here are all
non-negative numbers,

00:15:25.340 --> 00:15:30.740 align:middle line:84%
and this limsup here is now
going to be either infinite

00:15:30.740 --> 00:15:34.260 align:middle line:84%
or it's going to be some
real non-negative number.

00:15:34.260 --> 00:15:37.740 align:middle line:84%
This here is going
to be infinite.

00:15:37.740 --> 00:15:40.440 align:middle line:84%
Usually, we don't talk about
that it's converging if it's

00:15:40.440 --> 00:15:43.850 align:middle line:90%
infinite or it's some number.

00:15:43.850 --> 00:15:46.600 align:middle line:90%


00:15:46.600 --> 00:15:50.040 align:middle line:90%
Let's call it d, I guess.

00:15:50.040 --> 00:15:52.800 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:15:52.800 --> 00:16:01.260 align:middle line:84%
And the thing is that if you
said r equal to 1 over d--

00:16:01.260 --> 00:16:04.270 align:middle line:90%


00:16:04.270 --> 00:16:04.770 align:middle line:90%
sorry.

00:16:04.770 --> 00:16:08.860 align:middle line:90%


00:16:08.860 --> 00:16:12.400 align:middle line:84%
This is just a root test, the
adult version of the root test,

00:16:12.400 --> 00:16:15.540 align:middle line:84%
because this applies
to all sequences.

00:16:15.540 --> 00:16:18.040 align:middle line:90%
For any sequence, you have this.

00:16:18.040 --> 00:16:22.420 align:middle line:84%
For any sequence d-n, if
you're looking at this series,

00:16:22.420 --> 00:16:27.840 align:middle line:84%
you can look at this, and
it's either infinity or d.

00:16:27.840 --> 00:16:32.240 align:middle line:84%
And then if d here
is less than 1,

00:16:32.240 --> 00:16:34.180 align:middle line:90%
then the series is convergent.

00:16:34.180 --> 00:16:40.690 align:middle line:90%


00:16:40.690 --> 00:16:45.390 align:middle line:84%
If d is bigger than 1,
the series is divergent.

00:16:45.390 --> 00:16:51.970 align:middle line:90%


00:16:51.970 --> 00:16:55.510 align:middle line:84%
And if d is equal to
1, it's inconclusive.

00:16:55.510 --> 00:17:02.610 align:middle line:90%


00:17:02.610 --> 00:17:07.210 align:middle line:84%
The difference between this and
what we talked about last time

00:17:07.210 --> 00:17:12.810 align:middle line:84%
was that last time we assumed
that this thing here converged.

00:17:12.810 --> 00:17:17.170 align:middle line:84%
Here, I'm not assuming it, but
then I'm looking at the limsup

00:17:17.170 --> 00:17:18.690 align:middle line:90%
instead.

00:17:18.690 --> 00:17:24.810 align:middle line:84%
So this does give us a
number, and it's just

00:17:24.810 --> 00:17:29.530 align:middle line:84%
a matter of whether this
limsup is smaller than 1.

00:17:29.530 --> 00:17:31.990 align:middle line:84%
And then it's convergent
or bigger than 1,

00:17:31.990 --> 00:17:33.110 align:middle line:90%
then it's divergent.

00:17:33.110 --> 00:17:36.830 align:middle line:90%


00:17:36.830 --> 00:17:39.430 align:middle line:84%
Now I'll come back to
the proof, but the proof

00:17:39.430 --> 00:17:41.970 align:middle line:84%
is really kind of the
same as the one we gave.

00:17:41.970 --> 00:17:45.790 align:middle line:84%
The one we gave,
really, if you mimic

00:17:45.790 --> 00:17:50.430 align:middle line:84%
what we did in the
special case last time,

00:17:50.430 --> 00:17:54.030 align:middle line:84%
then the proof would
still apply to this case

00:17:54.030 --> 00:18:01.110 align:middle line:84%
here and give this
result. But let's

00:18:01.110 --> 00:18:06.130 align:middle line:84%
take this more fancy
version of the root test.

00:18:06.130 --> 00:18:07.740 align:middle line:90%
Let's take that for granted.

00:18:07.740 --> 00:18:15.870 align:middle line:90%


00:18:15.870 --> 00:18:20.870 align:middle line:84%
So now I have a power
series like this.

00:18:20.870 --> 00:18:31.750 align:middle line:84%
Just for clarity, I define
d-n to be just a-n, times x-n.

00:18:31.750 --> 00:18:42.880 align:middle line:84%
And I'm interested in is
for what x, for what x

00:18:42.880 --> 00:18:44.380 align:middle line:90%
does the power series converge?

00:18:44.380 --> 00:19:00.720 align:middle line:90%


00:19:00.720 --> 00:19:07.560 align:middle line:84%
So you are looking at limsup
of the n-th root of d-n

00:19:07.560 --> 00:19:16.155 align:middle line:84%
is a-n times x-n, and you take
the absolute value of that.

00:19:16.155 --> 00:19:18.640 align:middle line:84%
That's what you're
looking at, and you're

00:19:18.640 --> 00:19:23.120 align:middle line:84%
asking is this smaller
than 1 or bigger than 1?

00:19:23.120 --> 00:19:27.997 align:middle line:84%
But this thing here, right, this
is the same as limsup, right?

00:19:27.997 --> 00:19:29.580 align:middle line:84%
If you're looking
at this thing here--

00:19:29.580 --> 00:19:32.100 align:middle line:84%
let's do a little side
calculation-- if you're

00:19:32.100 --> 00:19:38.860 align:middle line:84%
looking at the n-th
root of a-n times x-n,

00:19:38.860 --> 00:19:44.780 align:middle line:84%
this thing here is the same as
the n-th root of this product

00:19:44.780 --> 00:19:45.280 align:middle line:90%
here.

00:19:45.280 --> 00:19:49.220 align:middle line:84%
Absolute value is the
same as this times

00:19:49.220 --> 00:19:53.500 align:middle line:90%
x absolute value to n.

00:19:53.500 --> 00:19:55.820 align:middle line:84%
And when you take
the n-th root, you

00:19:55.820 --> 00:19:59.820 align:middle line:84%
may as well take the n-th root
of each of those two factors

00:19:59.820 --> 00:20:01.460 align:middle line:90%
individually.

00:20:01.460 --> 00:20:02.920 align:middle line:90%
So this is what you get.

00:20:02.920 --> 00:20:08.020 align:middle line:90%


00:20:08.020 --> 00:20:11.500 align:middle line:84%
But this thing here, you
see, this thing here,

00:20:11.500 --> 00:20:15.380 align:middle line:84%
the n-th root-- this
is whatever it is.

00:20:15.380 --> 00:20:18.020 align:middle line:90%
Can't do much about that.

00:20:18.020 --> 00:20:20.740 align:middle line:84%
But this thing here,
that's just the norm

00:20:20.740 --> 00:20:24.540 align:middle line:84%
of x, and the norm of x has the
property that when you raise it

00:20:24.540 --> 00:20:26.580 align:middle line:84%
to the n-th power,
you're getting this.

00:20:26.580 --> 00:20:29.670 align:middle line:90%
So this is the n.

00:20:29.670 --> 00:20:32.310 align:middle line:84%
So this means that
this thing here

00:20:32.310 --> 00:20:41.920 align:middle line:84%
is the same as the norm of x
limsup of the n-th root of a-n.

00:20:41.920 --> 00:20:46.240 align:middle line:90%


00:20:46.240 --> 00:20:47.570 align:middle line:90%
Often you do it like this.

00:20:47.570 --> 00:20:49.130 align:middle line:90%
You don't have to do this.

00:20:49.130 --> 00:20:52.850 align:middle line:84%
It's usually clear anyway, but
often you write it like that.

00:20:52.850 --> 00:20:55.456 align:middle line:90%


00:20:55.456 --> 00:21:00.630 align:middle line:84%
So now what you do
is you are asking

00:21:00.630 --> 00:21:03.890 align:middle line:84%
when is this number
here smaller than 1?

00:21:03.890 --> 00:21:05.250 align:middle line:90%
When is it bigger than 1?

00:21:05.250 --> 00:21:08.490 align:middle line:90%


00:21:08.490 --> 00:21:10.750 align:middle line:84%
You see, now you
define something

00:21:10.750 --> 00:21:14.750 align:middle line:84%
that's called the
radius of convergence.

00:21:14.750 --> 00:21:17.150 align:middle line:90%
And so this is the following.

00:21:17.150 --> 00:21:24.790 align:middle line:90%
So the radius of convergence--

00:21:24.790 --> 00:21:30.850 align:middle line:84%
So this is just
radius of convergence.

00:21:30.850 --> 00:21:37.170 align:middle line:84%
The radius of convergence
is just a number,

00:21:37.170 --> 00:21:41.650 align:middle line:84%
and that number is
radius of convergence.

00:21:41.650 --> 00:21:44.430 align:middle line:84%
And we have to just
interpret it a little bit.

00:21:44.430 --> 00:21:51.800 align:middle line:84%
So it's 1 over limsup
of the n-th root.

00:21:51.800 --> 00:21:56.330 align:middle line:90%


00:21:56.330 --> 00:22:00.410 align:middle line:84%
This thing here could,
of course, be infinite.

00:22:00.410 --> 00:22:05.690 align:middle line:84%
If this is infinite, then the
radius, by definition, this here

00:22:05.690 --> 00:22:08.370 align:middle line:90%
would be 0.

00:22:08.370 --> 00:22:21.290 align:middle line:84%
Where this here is equal to
0 if this limsup is infinite.

00:22:21.290 --> 00:22:25.190 align:middle line:90%
And otherwise, it's always a-n.

00:22:25.190 --> 00:22:28.460 align:middle line:84%
Otherwise, there's one other
case you have to define,

00:22:28.460 --> 00:22:32.820 align:middle line:84%
that if it's infinite,
if the limsup--

00:22:32.820 --> 00:22:35.780 align:middle line:90%


00:22:35.780 --> 00:22:42.340 align:middle line:84%
sorry, this should be absolute
value if this limsup is zero.

00:22:42.340 --> 00:22:44.980 align:middle line:90%
otherwise.

00:22:44.980 --> 00:22:46.180 align:middle line:90%
Otherwise, there's nothing.

00:22:46.180 --> 00:22:49.060 align:middle line:84%
It's, well, that's the only
thing you have to comment,

00:22:49.060 --> 00:22:53.000 align:middle line:84%
because otherwise, it's
always a non-negative number.

00:22:53.000 --> 00:22:54.180 align:middle line:90%
But it could be 0.

00:22:54.180 --> 00:22:55.980 align:middle line:90%
It could be infinity.

00:22:55.980 --> 00:22:58.100 align:middle line:84%
But if it's any
other number, then it

00:22:58.100 --> 00:22:59.600 align:middle line:84%
is just what you
think it should be.

00:22:59.600 --> 00:23:02.460 align:middle line:90%
It's 1 over that number.

00:23:02.460 --> 00:23:09.940 align:middle line:84%
So r here is the radius
of convergence, OK?

00:23:09.940 --> 00:23:12.980 align:middle line:84%
And now the thing
is that now we have

00:23:12.980 --> 00:23:15.010 align:middle line:90%
the following symbol, picture.

00:23:15.010 --> 00:23:19.220 align:middle line:90%


00:23:19.220 --> 00:23:21.920 align:middle line:90%
So now we have that.

00:23:21.920 --> 00:23:23.510 align:middle line:90%
So you have this power series.

00:23:23.510 --> 00:23:28.320 align:middle line:90%


00:23:28.320 --> 00:23:30.660 align:middle line:84%
Again, it doesn't matter
what you start with.

00:23:30.660 --> 00:23:34.080 align:middle line:84%
Some matters what you start
with, but not the convergence.

00:23:34.080 --> 00:23:36.240 align:middle line:90%
So you have this power series.

00:23:36.240 --> 00:23:41.860 align:middle line:84%
You are forming r, this is
the radius of convergence.

00:23:41.860 --> 00:23:47.520 align:middle line:90%


00:23:47.520 --> 00:23:50.400 align:middle line:84%
And then the claim is--
and again, this could be 0.

00:23:50.400 --> 00:23:52.040 align:middle line:90%
It could be infinity.

00:23:52.040 --> 00:23:55.240 align:middle line:84%
But often, it's
just a real number,

00:23:55.240 --> 00:23:58.480 align:middle line:84%
a non-negative real number,
positive real number.

00:23:58.480 --> 00:24:04.640 align:middle line:84%
And so, it's saying that if you
take the interval here around 0,

00:24:04.640 --> 00:24:12.120 align:middle line:84%
in the interval from minus r
to r, then inside this interval

00:24:12.120 --> 00:24:16.320 align:middle line:84%
here, inside here
when x is in here,

00:24:16.320 --> 00:24:22.840 align:middle line:84%
then the power
series is convergent.

00:24:22.840 --> 00:24:25.610 align:middle line:90%


00:24:25.610 --> 00:24:32.510 align:middle line:84%
And when x is here or here,
power series is divergent.

00:24:32.510 --> 00:24:40.210 align:middle line:90%


00:24:40.210 --> 00:24:45.810 align:middle line:84%
And then when x is here or
here at those two points,

00:24:45.810 --> 00:24:50.930 align:middle line:84%
then it's unclear and
further test is needed.

00:24:50.930 --> 00:24:52.060 align:middle line:90%
Further test is needed.

00:24:52.060 --> 00:24:56.530 align:middle line:90%


00:24:56.530 --> 00:24:57.460 align:middle line:90%
Tests are needed.

00:24:57.460 --> 00:25:01.730 align:middle line:90%


00:25:01.730 --> 00:25:03.370 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:25:03.370 --> 00:25:04.650 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:25:04.650 --> 00:25:07.770 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Starting from
the last step on the left

00:25:07.770 --> 00:25:10.210 align:middle line:84%
to get to this
equation for r, are you

00:25:10.210 --> 00:25:14.450 align:middle line:84%
just essentially saying that
less than or equal to 1 or less

00:25:14.450 --> 00:25:15.870 align:middle line:90%
than or equal to 1?

00:25:15.870 --> 00:25:18.530 align:middle line:84%
But then we only care
about one x less than 1

00:25:18.530 --> 00:25:19.750 align:middle line:90%
because we need that.

00:25:19.750 --> 00:25:21.333 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING: Yeah,
so that's right.

00:25:21.333 --> 00:25:22.490 align:middle line:90%
So let's come to the proof.

00:25:22.490 --> 00:25:22.990 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:25:22.990 --> 00:25:24.610 align:middle line:84%
So this is what
you're talking about.

00:25:24.610 --> 00:25:27.650 align:middle line:90%


00:25:27.650 --> 00:25:33.510 align:middle line:84%
So this is the radius
of convergence.

00:25:33.510 --> 00:25:39.570 align:middle line:84%
And so as you say,
all we need to do is--

00:25:39.570 --> 00:25:44.650 align:middle line:84%
we know from the more fancy
version of the ratio test,

00:25:44.650 --> 00:25:49.850 align:middle line:84%
that is, in terms of
limsup, we know that--

00:25:49.850 --> 00:25:53.470 align:middle line:90%
So proof here.

00:25:53.470 --> 00:25:59.200 align:middle line:84%
Power series is convergent
by the ratio test.

00:25:59.200 --> 00:26:03.870 align:middle line:90%


00:26:03.870 --> 00:26:05.110 align:middle line:90%
Not ratio test, sorry.

00:26:05.110 --> 00:26:09.190 align:middle line:90%
The root test, by the root test.

00:26:09.190 --> 00:26:14.310 align:middle line:84%
So again, the version,
the limsup version--

00:26:14.310 --> 00:26:17.350 align:middle line:84%
not the one I talked about
last time, but this one we just

00:26:17.350 --> 00:26:19.110 align:middle line:90%
talked about--

00:26:19.110 --> 00:26:23.840 align:middle line:84%
by the limsup version
of the root test.

00:26:23.840 --> 00:26:28.640 align:middle line:84%
Then the power series is
convergent if this thing here--

00:26:28.640 --> 00:26:30.840 align:middle line:84%
so this means that
this thing here--

00:26:30.840 --> 00:26:41.960 align:middle line:84%
so if this thing here,
limsup of an n-th root.

00:26:41.960 --> 00:26:47.160 align:middle line:84%
If this thing here is less
than 1, it's divergent.

00:26:47.160 --> 00:27:01.160 align:middle line:84%
If this thing here
is bigger than 1,

00:27:01.160 --> 00:27:15.420 align:middle line:84%
and it's inconclusive if this
thing here is equal to 1 here.

00:27:15.420 --> 00:27:16.460 align:middle line:90%
It's inconclusive.

00:27:16.460 --> 00:27:20.460 align:middle line:90%


00:27:20.460 --> 00:27:27.500 align:middle line:84%
But now you see that this here
just means that the norm of x

00:27:27.500 --> 00:27:30.560 align:middle line:84%
should be smaller
than 1 over that.

00:27:30.560 --> 00:27:36.660 align:middle line:84%
So this here is the same as
saying that the norm of x

00:27:36.660 --> 00:27:42.580 align:middle line:84%
is smaller than r, the
radius of convergence.

00:27:42.580 --> 00:27:46.620 align:middle line:84%
This is equivalent to
saying that the norm of x

00:27:46.620 --> 00:27:51.660 align:middle line:90%
is bigger than r.

00:27:51.660 --> 00:27:56.500 align:middle line:84%
And this here is equivalent
to saying that the norm of x

00:27:56.500 --> 00:27:57.620 align:middle line:90%
is equal to r.

00:27:57.620 --> 00:28:07.500 align:middle line:90%


00:28:07.500 --> 00:28:10.440 align:middle line:84%
So that's the radius
of convergence.

00:28:10.440 --> 00:28:12.700 align:middle line:90%
So this is, like, a priori.

00:28:12.700 --> 00:28:16.540 align:middle line:84%
This is not at all
clear that it couldn't

00:28:16.540 --> 00:28:18.630 align:middle line:84%
be-- that a power
series couldn't

00:28:18.630 --> 00:28:23.030 align:middle line:84%
be convergent for some
sort of discrete set of x.

00:28:23.030 --> 00:28:24.550 align:middle line:90%
But that's not the case.

00:28:24.550 --> 00:28:26.930 align:middle line:84%
It's convergent
on some interval.

00:28:26.930 --> 00:28:31.310 align:middle line:84%
It's unclear at the
end of that interval,

00:28:31.310 --> 00:28:33.510 align:middle line:84%
but it is convergence
on the interval,

00:28:33.510 --> 00:28:36.030 align:middle line:84%
and divergent outside
that interval.

00:28:36.030 --> 00:28:43.430 align:middle line:84%
Now that interval could be
just 0 or it could be all over.

00:28:43.430 --> 00:28:45.860 align:middle line:84%
But it is also
symmetric around zero.

00:28:45.860 --> 00:28:48.810 align:middle line:90%


00:28:48.810 --> 00:28:52.310 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: But when we bring
that over, isn't it 1 over?

00:28:52.310 --> 00:28:53.480 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: Right.

00:28:53.480 --> 00:28:56.110 align:middle line:90%
So it's 1 over this here.

00:28:56.110 --> 00:29:00.490 align:middle line:84%
But remember how r was
defined. r is up there.

00:29:00.490 --> 00:29:00.990 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:29:00.990 --> 00:29:04.990 align:middle line:90%


00:29:04.990 --> 00:29:07.710 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:29:07.710 --> 00:29:15.510 align:middle line:84%
Now let me just say
a word about why

00:29:15.510 --> 00:29:20.130 align:middle line:84%
does the proof
from last time, why

00:29:20.130 --> 00:29:22.930 align:middle line:90%
does it really prove this more?

00:29:22.930 --> 00:29:27.370 align:middle line:84%
I mean, the argument
we gave last time,

00:29:27.370 --> 00:29:31.250 align:middle line:90%
why does it give you this?

00:29:31.250 --> 00:29:33.070 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it's much
more satisfying,

00:29:33.070 --> 00:29:36.650 align:middle line:84%
this version of the
root test, because it

00:29:36.650 --> 00:29:39.650 align:middle line:90%
applies to any series.

00:29:39.650 --> 00:29:41.370 align:middle line:84%
Because otherwise,
we talked about

00:29:41.370 --> 00:29:43.790 align:middle line:84%
whether some ratio
was convergent,

00:29:43.790 --> 00:29:45.310 align:middle line:90%
but it may not converge.

00:29:45.310 --> 00:29:48.050 align:middle line:90%
So this is much more satisfying.

00:29:48.050 --> 00:29:53.010 align:middle line:84%
So suppose, again, you
have a series like this.

00:29:53.010 --> 00:29:57.250 align:middle line:84%
And so now you're
looking at limsup.

00:29:57.250 --> 00:30:01.570 align:middle line:84%
So this is, again,
this is the root test.

00:30:01.570 --> 00:30:06.670 align:middle line:90%
Root test version.

00:30:06.670 --> 00:30:10.970 align:middle line:90%
Let's call it version 2.0.

00:30:10.970 --> 00:30:15.820 align:middle line:84%
And so you take a series
serious like this,

00:30:15.820 --> 00:30:21.820 align:middle line:84%
and it's looking
at limsup, and then

00:30:21.820 --> 00:30:27.440 align:middle line:84%
the n-th root of the
absolute value of the n.

00:30:27.440 --> 00:30:30.020 align:middle line:90%


00:30:30.020 --> 00:30:36.940 align:middle line:84%
And again, it's saying that if
this thing here is less than 1,

00:30:36.940 --> 00:30:37.900 align:middle line:90%
it's convergent.

00:30:37.900 --> 00:30:40.860 align:middle line:90%


00:30:40.860 --> 00:30:46.700 align:middle line:84%
If it's bigger than
1, it's divergent.

00:30:46.700 --> 00:30:49.760 align:middle line:84%
And if it's equal to
1, it's inconclusive.

00:30:49.760 --> 00:30:56.160 align:middle line:90%


00:30:56.160 --> 00:31:02.160 align:middle line:84%
Now, let's try to see why
this here is the case.

00:31:02.160 --> 00:31:21.240 align:middle line:84%
So proof of root
test version 2.0.

00:31:21.240 --> 00:31:25.500 align:middle line:84%
Maybe I won't do all of
it, but let's just look at.

00:31:25.500 --> 00:31:28.040 align:middle line:84%
Because in a minute, you
see that it's really kind

00:31:28.040 --> 00:31:30.080 align:middle line:90%
of super similar to last time.

00:31:30.080 --> 00:31:43.200 align:middle line:84%
So suppose that this limsup
of the n-th root here, of d-n,

00:31:43.200 --> 00:31:50.080 align:middle line:84%
suppose that this thing here
is equal to some d, which

00:31:50.080 --> 00:31:53.200 align:middle line:90%
is strictly less than 1.

00:31:53.200 --> 00:31:54.280 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:31:54.280 --> 00:32:02.800 align:middle line:84%
So this means that
there exists--

00:32:02.800 --> 00:32:18.730 align:middle line:84%
so if you will, choose d bar
with d less than d bar strictly

00:32:18.730 --> 00:32:21.310 align:middle line:90%
less than 1.

00:32:21.310 --> 00:32:22.980 align:middle line:90%
So I can choose it like this.

00:32:22.980 --> 00:32:26.530 align:middle line:90%


00:32:26.530 --> 00:32:30.810 align:middle line:84%
But now you see that if I
choose it like this, then

00:32:30.810 --> 00:32:31.500 align:middle line:90%
there exists--

00:32:31.500 --> 00:32:34.530 align:middle line:90%


00:32:34.530 --> 00:32:40.970 align:middle line:84%
so remember, let's just
remind ourselves that--

00:32:40.970 --> 00:32:44.050 align:middle line:90%
how was the limsup defined?

00:32:44.050 --> 00:32:49.650 align:middle line:84%
The limsup was
defined to be that you

00:32:49.650 --> 00:32:51.790 align:middle line:90%
take this new sequence--

00:32:51.790 --> 00:32:55.930 align:middle line:84%
So you're taking
this sequence here.

00:32:55.930 --> 00:33:00.330 align:middle line:84%
So you're taking
these guys here.

00:33:00.330 --> 00:33:04.010 align:middle line:84%
So you're looking at
now these guys here,

00:33:04.010 --> 00:33:10.870 align:middle line:84%
and you define a sequence
that is like the sup,

00:33:10.870 --> 00:33:17.750 align:middle line:84%
starting at the n-th
guy, and like this here.

00:33:17.750 --> 00:33:21.830 align:middle line:84%
So this here is n
plus 1, et cetera.

00:33:21.830 --> 00:33:24.170 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:33:24.170 --> 00:33:27.762 align:middle line:90%
This is the sup of the tail.

00:33:27.762 --> 00:33:30.910 align:middle line:90%
And so that was sup on--

00:33:30.910 --> 00:33:32.550 align:middle line:84%
as you're going
further out, you're

00:33:32.550 --> 00:33:34.730 align:middle line:90%
taking sup over smaller sets.

00:33:34.730 --> 00:33:38.550 align:middle line:90%
So this sequence going down.

00:33:38.550 --> 00:33:42.230 align:middle line:84%
So now if this
limit here is sup d,

00:33:42.230 --> 00:33:45.030 align:middle line:84%
which is strictly
less than d bar,

00:33:45.030 --> 00:33:47.230 align:middle line:90%
then it means that they exist.

00:33:47.230 --> 00:33:55.110 align:middle line:84%
So there exists capital N.
So that if little n is bigger

00:33:55.110 --> 00:33:58.590 align:middle line:84%
than capital N, then
all of these guys

00:33:58.590 --> 00:34:02.880 align:middle line:90%
here is less than d bar, right?

00:34:02.880 --> 00:34:05.490 align:middle line:90%


00:34:05.490 --> 00:34:08.800 align:middle line:84%
So if this here, then
all of these guys

00:34:08.800 --> 00:34:12.659 align:middle line:84%
here is less than
or equal to d bar.

00:34:12.659 --> 00:34:17.150 align:middle line:84%
This is if little n, if you're
starting that far out, right?

00:34:17.150 --> 00:34:21.260 align:middle line:90%


00:34:21.260 --> 00:34:24.199 align:middle line:84%
So you have that when
n is bigger than this,

00:34:24.199 --> 00:34:25.540 align:middle line:90%
you have that this.

00:34:25.540 --> 00:34:30.560 align:middle line:84%
So you have that for all
these guys here, d-n,

00:34:30.560 --> 00:34:35.100 align:middle line:84%
the n-th root is less
than d bar-- less than

00:34:35.100 --> 00:34:39.440 align:middle line:90%
or equal to d bar.

00:34:39.440 --> 00:34:43.780 align:middle line:84%
But now you take the
n-th power on both sides,

00:34:43.780 --> 00:34:49.280 align:middle line:84%
so you have that the n absolute
value is less than d bar,

00:34:49.280 --> 00:34:51.159 align:middle line:90%
the n power.

00:34:51.159 --> 00:34:55.900 align:middle line:84%
This here is, d, this isn't
even actually non-negative,

00:34:55.900 --> 00:34:58.520 align:middle line:84%
so you don't even need
this absolute value sign.

00:34:58.520 --> 00:35:00.040 align:middle line:90%
So you're having this.

00:35:00.040 --> 00:35:03.680 align:middle line:84%
But this is a number that
is strictly less than 1,

00:35:03.680 --> 00:35:06.686 align:middle line:84%
so this here is a
geometric series.

00:35:06.686 --> 00:35:22.880 align:middle line:84%
Geometric series where
d bar is less than 1.

00:35:22.880 --> 00:35:26.180 align:middle line:84%
So it is a convergent
geometric series, right?

00:35:26.180 --> 00:35:29.140 align:middle line:84%
So this is, you see, that it's
basically the same proof we

00:35:29.140 --> 00:35:29.880 align:middle line:90%
did last time.

00:35:29.880 --> 00:35:32.633 align:middle line:84%
But last time, we were assuming
that some ratio was converging

00:35:32.633 --> 00:35:37.720 align:middle line:84%
or we were assuming that this
here converges to something,

00:35:37.720 --> 00:35:39.620 align:middle line:84%
but you don't need
it to converge.

00:35:39.620 --> 00:35:46.580 align:middle line:84%
You just need that the
limsup is less than 1.

00:35:46.580 --> 00:35:51.300 align:middle line:84%
And so likewise, if you examine
what this case here say, then

00:35:51.300 --> 00:35:54.900 align:middle line:84%
just like last time, it's
going to say that if this here

00:35:54.900 --> 00:35:58.820 align:middle line:84%
is bigger than 1, then the
ordinary element doesn't even

00:35:58.820 --> 00:36:00.806 align:middle line:90%
go to 0.

00:36:00.806 --> 00:36:05.650 align:middle line:84%
So it fails the most basic
test for being convergent

00:36:05.650 --> 00:36:08.390 align:middle line:84%
And that was just
like last time, also.

00:36:08.390 --> 00:36:10.670 align:middle line:90%
And again, the advantage--

00:36:10.670 --> 00:36:12.990 align:middle line:84%
I think you were the one
that was asking yesterday.

00:36:12.990 --> 00:36:16.570 align:middle line:84%
I mean, last time this was the
ratio test and the root test,

00:36:16.570 --> 00:36:18.910 align:middle line:84%
and like in the ratio
test, it's something

00:36:18.910 --> 00:36:25.710 align:middle line:84%
about that the next element is
going down with some fraction.

00:36:25.710 --> 00:36:29.570 align:middle line:84%
And you very much see that
this here works for all series.

00:36:29.570 --> 00:36:31.950 align:middle line:84%
And it's really just
because you don't

00:36:31.950 --> 00:36:34.350 align:middle line:84%
compare the element to
the next, but you're

00:36:34.350 --> 00:36:35.960 align:middle line:90%
comparing it to this fixed.

00:36:35.960 --> 00:36:38.950 align:middle line:90%


00:36:38.950 --> 00:36:41.070 align:middle line:84%
series, which is a
geometric series.

00:36:41.070 --> 00:36:45.750 align:middle line:90%


00:36:45.750 --> 00:36:59.510 align:middle line:84%
So that's the real version,
so to speak, of the root test.

00:36:59.510 --> 00:37:05.400 align:middle line:84%
So now let's talk a little
bit more about power series.

00:37:05.400 --> 00:37:11.610 align:middle line:90%


00:37:11.610 --> 00:37:17.290 align:middle line:84%
So like this one function that
is particularly important,

00:37:17.290 --> 00:37:20.870 align:middle line:84%
and I mean, all of these basic
functions are, of course,

00:37:20.870 --> 00:37:23.850 align:middle line:84%
important, but they
are somewhat similar.

00:37:23.850 --> 00:37:27.880 align:middle line:84%
And the one I want to talk about
is the exponential function.

00:37:27.880 --> 00:37:36.170 align:middle line:90%


00:37:36.170 --> 00:37:39.230 align:middle line:84%
And there's various way
that you could define,

00:37:39.230 --> 00:37:41.730 align:middle line:84%
so what is the
exponential function?

00:37:41.730 --> 00:37:43.930 align:middle line:84%
There's various ways
that you could define

00:37:43.930 --> 00:37:45.310 align:middle line:90%
the exponential function.

00:37:45.310 --> 00:37:48.630 align:middle line:84%
You can define it, like,
two that comes to mind.

00:37:48.630 --> 00:37:50.170 align:middle line:90%
But there's others, too.

00:37:50.170 --> 00:37:53.530 align:middle line:84%
One is that you could define
it to be a function that's

00:37:53.530 --> 00:37:56.490 align:middle line:84%
satisfying a certain
differential equation,

00:37:56.490 --> 00:37:59.130 align:middle line:84%
and that would be a
good way of defining it.

00:37:59.130 --> 00:38:00.850 align:middle line:84%
Another way of
defining it, which

00:38:00.850 --> 00:38:02.780 align:middle line:84%
is more relevant to
what we're doing here,

00:38:02.780 --> 00:38:06.220 align:middle line:84%
is defining it as
a power series.

00:38:06.220 --> 00:38:18.220 align:middle line:84%
So I'm looking at e to the x,
and I'm looking at e to the x.

00:38:18.220 --> 00:38:23.822 align:middle line:84%
So I define E, capital E of x,
as this power series that we

00:38:23.822 --> 00:38:24.530 align:middle line:90%
looked at before.

00:38:24.530 --> 00:38:29.792 align:middle line:90%


00:38:29.792 --> 00:38:34.660 align:middle line:84%
Now I want to prove
that this here is really

00:38:34.660 --> 00:38:36.380 align:middle line:90%
what you should think of.

00:38:36.380 --> 00:38:38.810 align:middle line:84%
This here is the
exponential function.

00:38:38.810 --> 00:38:41.940 align:middle line:90%


00:38:41.940 --> 00:38:44.520 align:middle line:84%
But what does it mean
that is is exponential?

00:38:44.520 --> 00:38:54.440 align:middle line:84%
I want to show that this is
the exponential function.

00:38:54.440 --> 00:38:56.460 align:middle line:90%
So what do I mean by?

00:38:56.460 --> 00:39:01.640 align:middle line:84%
I mean, of course I
could define any function

00:39:01.640 --> 00:39:04.160 align:middle line:84%
to be the exponential
function, but there

00:39:04.160 --> 00:39:07.720 align:middle line:84%
are certain properties of
the exponential function

00:39:07.720 --> 00:39:09.340 align:middle line:90%
that you would want.

00:39:09.340 --> 00:39:13.520 align:middle line:90%


00:39:13.520 --> 00:39:23.400 align:middle line:84%
Well, the first thing I observe
is that E of 0 is equal to--

00:39:23.400 --> 00:39:30.720 align:middle line:84%
if x is 0, then all of these are
0, except when n is equal to 0.

00:39:30.720 --> 00:39:36.180 align:middle line:84%
And then x to the 0, this
here, is, by definition, one.

00:39:36.180 --> 00:39:41.060 align:middle line:84%
And this is 0, factorial
is by definition one.

00:39:41.060 --> 00:39:46.760 align:middle line:84%
So this here is
1, by definition.

00:39:46.760 --> 00:39:50.800 align:middle line:84%
And we know already, by the way,
that this here we have already

00:39:50.800 --> 00:39:54.520 align:middle line:84%
seen that the radius of
convergence for this power

00:39:54.520 --> 00:40:03.690 align:middle line:84%
series, of convergence
is equal to infinity.

00:40:03.690 --> 00:40:07.330 align:middle line:84%
We have already seen that, so
it's a well-defined function

00:40:07.330 --> 00:40:08.390 align:middle line:90%
for all x.

00:40:08.390 --> 00:40:14.490 align:middle line:90%


00:40:14.490 --> 00:40:27.530 align:middle line:84%
So next time we will show
that if you define it

00:40:27.530 --> 00:40:31.850 align:middle line:84%
like that, that this function
here, defined like that,

00:40:31.850 --> 00:40:40.470 align:middle line:84%
has a property that x of E to x
plus y is equal to this product.

00:40:40.470 --> 00:40:49.670 align:middle line:90%


00:40:49.670 --> 00:40:52.850 align:middle line:84%
Well, the first thing
I can observe is--

00:40:52.850 --> 00:40:56.090 align:middle line:84%
I haven't really gotten to the
property yet, but at the moment

00:40:56.090 --> 00:40:59.740 align:middle line:84%
I'm just examining that
particular function,

00:40:59.740 --> 00:41:03.700 align:middle line:90%
some properties that it has.

00:41:03.700 --> 00:41:05.540 align:middle line:84%
And so the first
thing I will observe

00:41:05.540 --> 00:41:10.480 align:middle line:84%
is that if x is positive
or non-negative, right,

00:41:10.480 --> 00:41:12.800 align:middle line:84%
then all of these
numbers are non-negative.

00:41:12.800 --> 00:41:14.800 align:middle line:84%
So you're summing
non-negative numbers.

00:41:14.800 --> 00:41:17.020 align:middle line:90%
So the sum is non-negative.

00:41:17.020 --> 00:41:25.820 align:middle line:84%
So if x is bigger or equal to
0, then it implies that E of x

00:41:25.820 --> 00:41:30.620 align:middle line:84%
is bigger, is actually
strictly positive.

00:41:30.620 --> 00:41:34.800 align:middle line:84%
In fact, the smallest one
is where x was equal to 0.

00:41:34.800 --> 00:41:38.140 align:middle line:84%
But in that case,
you got one, right?

00:41:38.140 --> 00:41:43.380 align:middle line:84%
Now if x is negative,
then it's not super clear.

00:41:43.380 --> 00:41:45.820 align:middle line:90%
But if x is negative--

00:41:45.820 --> 00:41:48.700 align:middle line:84%
some of these numbers that
you'll be summing are positive

00:41:48.700 --> 00:41:51.740 align:middle line:84%
and some of them are negative,
so it's not at all clear

00:41:51.740 --> 00:41:53.780 align:middle line:90%
what happened to the sum.

00:41:53.780 --> 00:41:57.580 align:middle line:84%
But if you grant me
this for the moment,

00:41:57.580 --> 00:42:01.920 align:middle line:84%
this relationship here,
then we would have that E

00:42:01.920 --> 00:42:04.800 align:middle line:90%
to the x minus E--

00:42:04.800 --> 00:42:08.500 align:middle line:90%
minus, sorry, E in x minus x--

00:42:08.500 --> 00:42:10.190 align:middle line:90%
So that's the same as--

00:42:10.190 --> 00:42:14.160 align:middle line:90%


00:42:14.160 --> 00:42:19.120 align:middle line:84%
so E of 0, which I
already know is one,

00:42:19.120 --> 00:42:24.960 align:middle line:84%
this here can think
about that as x minus x.

00:42:24.960 --> 00:42:29.270 align:middle line:84%
Or, if you will, to think
about it as x plus minus x.

00:42:29.270 --> 00:42:31.840 align:middle line:90%


00:42:31.840 --> 00:42:36.120 align:middle line:84%
And now, if you grant
me this thing here

00:42:36.120 --> 00:42:39.880 align:middle line:84%
that we prove next time,
then I can write this

00:42:39.880 --> 00:42:46.522 align:middle line:90%
as E of x times E of minus x.

00:42:46.522 --> 00:42:47.022 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:42:47.022 --> 00:42:53.492 align:middle line:90%


00:42:53.492 --> 00:42:59.970 align:middle line:84%
And now if x here is negative,
then of course minus x

00:42:59.970 --> 00:43:00.990 align:middle line:90%
is positive.

00:43:00.990 --> 00:43:04.770 align:middle line:90%


00:43:04.770 --> 00:43:09.490 align:middle line:84%
So now I know by this thing
here that this here is positive.

00:43:09.490 --> 00:43:13.190 align:middle line:84%
And so, since the product
of these two things is 1,

00:43:13.190 --> 00:43:16.730 align:middle line:84%
this here must be strictly
positive as well, right?

00:43:16.730 --> 00:43:22.470 align:middle line:84%
So this implies that E to the
x is also strictly positive.

00:43:22.470 --> 00:43:26.098 align:middle line:90%


00:43:26.098 --> 00:43:28.510 align:middle line:84%
So this is just a
couple of observations.

00:43:28.510 --> 00:43:30.530 align:middle line:84%
Now, of course, I'm
using that relationship

00:43:30.530 --> 00:43:32.130 align:middle line:84%
that I haven't
established yet, but I

00:43:32.130 --> 00:43:35.170 align:middle line:90%
will establish that next time.

00:43:35.170 --> 00:43:46.690 align:middle line:84%
The next thing is that I
want to define the number E,

00:43:46.690 --> 00:43:50.130 align:middle line:90%
so E, that is 2.7, whatever.

00:43:50.130 --> 00:43:52.690 align:middle line:90%
I don't remember.

00:43:52.690 --> 00:43:55.270 align:middle line:90%
So E we define--

00:43:55.270 --> 00:44:02.990 align:middle line:84%
so little e, so I define it as
this function here evaluated

00:44:02.990 --> 00:44:04.030 align:middle line:90%
in one.

00:44:04.030 --> 00:44:04.530 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:44:04.530 --> 00:44:10.630 align:middle line:90%


00:44:10.630 --> 00:44:13.230 align:middle line:84%
So I have my
function, capital E,

00:44:13.230 --> 00:44:19.230 align:middle line:84%
but I want to define a
second function that is e.

00:44:19.230 --> 00:44:32.190 align:middle line:84%
So I want to define a
second function, and that

00:44:32.190 --> 00:44:36.630 align:middle line:84%
is e to the x,
like this, and that

00:44:36.630 --> 00:44:40.150 align:middle line:84%
should have the
kind of properties

00:44:40.150 --> 00:44:43.370 align:middle line:90%
that you think it should have.

00:44:43.370 --> 00:44:48.330 align:middle line:84%
But first, before I do
that, let me just think.

00:44:48.330 --> 00:44:58.280 align:middle line:84%
If you take e to
the power m here,

00:44:58.280 --> 00:45:00.790 align:middle line:90%
let's say that m is an integer.

00:45:00.790 --> 00:45:07.280 align:middle line:90%


00:45:07.280 --> 00:45:15.830 align:middle line:84%
This here should just
be e times e m times.

00:45:15.830 --> 00:45:20.720 align:middle line:90%


00:45:20.720 --> 00:45:27.280 align:middle line:84%
Note that this here, I
can, of course, write as e.

00:45:27.280 --> 00:45:35.270 align:middle line:84%
This is what e is, so I can
write it as this here, m times.

00:45:35.270 --> 00:45:38.000 align:middle line:90%


00:45:38.000 --> 00:45:43.400 align:middle line:84%
But now I can use this here that
I will prove next time again.

00:45:43.400 --> 00:45:50.340 align:middle line:84%
So if I take E of 1 times
E of 1, then that's E of 2.

00:45:50.340 --> 00:45:56.140 align:middle line:84%
And if I take E three
times, that is E of 3.

00:45:56.140 --> 00:46:03.580 align:middle line:84%
So this thing here is actually
the same as capital E of m,

00:46:03.580 --> 00:46:05.220 align:middle line:90%
right?

00:46:05.220 --> 00:46:08.500 align:middle line:90%
So I have that.

00:46:08.500 --> 00:46:16.180 align:middle line:84%
By definition, e to the 0, this
here I'm setting equal to 1.

00:46:16.180 --> 00:46:24.180 align:middle line:84%
But I already have that one was
equal to this capital E in 0.

00:46:24.180 --> 00:46:26.880 align:middle line:90%


00:46:26.880 --> 00:46:30.390 align:middle line:84%
Now what about if m here
is a negative integer?

00:46:30.390 --> 00:46:41.020 align:middle line:90%


00:46:41.020 --> 00:46:45.020 align:middle line:84%
So suppose that m here
is a negative integer.

00:46:45.020 --> 00:46:48.000 align:middle line:90%
Suppose that m here is negative.

00:46:48.000 --> 00:46:52.190 align:middle line:90%


00:46:52.190 --> 00:46:56.230 align:middle line:90%
What should e to the m here be?

00:46:56.230 --> 00:47:04.510 align:middle line:84%
This here is just 1
over e to the minus m.

00:47:04.510 --> 00:47:11.330 align:middle line:84%
OK, minus m is a positive
integer, so this makes sense.

00:47:11.330 --> 00:47:14.310 align:middle line:90%


00:47:14.310 --> 00:47:21.230 align:middle line:84%
Now, if you're looking
at e to the-- again,

00:47:21.230 --> 00:47:24.970 align:middle line:84%
using this
relationship here, e--

00:47:24.970 --> 00:47:27.750 align:middle line:84%
and in fact, the
one we just did.

00:47:27.750 --> 00:47:32.590 align:middle line:84%
So this is on
integers, and this here

00:47:32.590 --> 00:47:37.700 align:middle line:84%
is now equal to E of
0, which is equal to 1.

00:47:37.700 --> 00:47:40.870 align:middle line:90%


00:47:40.870 --> 00:47:44.510 align:middle line:84%
And this is, by that
relationship over there,

00:47:44.510 --> 00:47:49.490 align:middle line:90%
it's E of m times E of minus m.

00:47:49.490 --> 00:47:55.490 align:middle line:84%
And so you see that this
implies that E of minus M

00:47:55.490 --> 00:47:59.370 align:middle line:84%
is equal to 1 over
E of m, by just

00:47:59.370 --> 00:48:02.170 align:middle line:90%
dividing this on both sides.

00:48:02.170 --> 00:48:07.810 align:middle line:84%
So you have this, and this thing
here, but this thing here--

00:48:07.810 --> 00:48:10.210 align:middle line:84%
sorry, this is
not what I wanted.

00:48:10.210 --> 00:48:13.590 align:middle line:84%
If I take m negative, I
just use the other one.

00:48:13.590 --> 00:48:14.610 align:middle line:90%
Sorry.

00:48:14.610 --> 00:48:23.990 align:middle line:84%
E of M is equal to 1 over
E of minus m, like that.

00:48:23.990 --> 00:48:26.930 align:middle line:90%


00:48:26.930 --> 00:48:29.530 align:middle line:84%
M was supposed to
be negative, so this

00:48:29.530 --> 00:48:32.930 align:middle line:84%
means that minus M is
a positive integer.

00:48:32.930 --> 00:48:36.310 align:middle line:84%
And this one here
is then this one.

00:48:36.310 --> 00:48:39.050 align:middle line:84%
I know that this
here already agree

00:48:39.050 --> 00:48:47.420 align:middle line:90%
with this little function of e.

00:48:47.420 --> 00:48:52.740 align:middle line:84%
So you see that this thing here
agrees with e to the power m.

00:48:52.740 --> 00:48:55.995 align:middle line:90%


00:48:55.995 --> 00:49:02.220 align:middle line:84%
Because we define it like this,
and now just checking that also

00:49:02.220 --> 00:49:05.140 align:middle line:84%
on the negative integer,
this function here

00:49:05.140 --> 00:49:07.500 align:middle line:90%
and this function here agree.

00:49:07.500 --> 00:49:08.740 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:49:08.740 --> 00:49:12.140 align:middle line:84%
So I now have these two
different functions,

00:49:12.140 --> 00:49:14.280 align:middle line:84%
but one I haven't
really defined yet.

00:49:14.280 --> 00:49:17.460 align:middle line:84%
I've only defined it
now on all integers.

00:49:17.460 --> 00:49:21.940 align:middle line:84%
But so far, these
two functions agree.

00:49:21.940 --> 00:49:28.060 align:middle line:84%
Now what I also should have
is that I should have--

00:49:28.060 --> 00:49:30.330 align:middle line:84%
so suppose you're looking
at a rational number.

00:49:30.330 --> 00:49:34.700 align:middle line:90%


00:49:34.700 --> 00:49:36.680 align:middle line:84%
So suppose you take
a rational number.

00:49:36.680 --> 00:49:39.000 align:middle line:84%
Remember, we usually
write a rational number.

00:49:39.000 --> 00:49:42.540 align:middle line:84%
So suppose that q here
is a rational number.

00:49:42.540 --> 00:49:52.460 align:middle line:84%
We usually write a rational
number as an element in set.

00:49:52.460 --> 00:49:53.540 align:middle line:90%
So it could be negative.

00:49:53.540 --> 00:49:54.960 align:middle line:90%
It could be 0.

00:49:54.960 --> 00:50:00.280 align:middle line:84%
And n here is a
positive integer, so

00:50:00.280 --> 00:50:01.460 align:middle line:90%
a fraction like this.

00:50:01.460 --> 00:50:05.200 align:middle line:90%


00:50:05.200 --> 00:50:10.560 align:middle line:90%
Now what should e of q be?

00:50:10.560 --> 00:50:13.360 align:middle line:90%


00:50:13.360 --> 00:50:17.880 align:middle line:84%
Well, e of q, this
here should be--

00:50:17.880 --> 00:50:20.080 align:middle line:84%
how you would think about
it is that it really

00:50:20.080 --> 00:50:21.540 align:middle line:90%
should be something.

00:50:21.540 --> 00:50:24.120 align:middle line:90%


00:50:24.120 --> 00:50:25.620 align:middle line:90%
This here should be a number.

00:50:25.620 --> 00:50:29.360 align:middle line:84%
Should be a number, alpha,
and this should have

00:50:29.360 --> 00:50:33.200 align:middle line:90%
the property that is positive.

00:50:33.200 --> 00:50:38.280 align:middle line:84%
And it should have the property,
so let's just write it.

00:50:38.280 --> 00:50:43.250 align:middle line:90%
So e of q, this is m over n.

00:50:43.250 --> 00:50:47.410 align:middle line:84%
It should have the property
that if you raise it--

00:50:47.410 --> 00:50:52.490 align:middle line:84%
alpha here, suppose you were
raising it to the power n,

00:50:52.490 --> 00:50:55.130 align:middle line:84%
then you should get this
number that we have already

00:50:55.130 --> 00:50:57.330 align:middle line:90%
defined, right?

00:50:57.330 --> 00:51:04.422 align:middle line:84%
So it should be positive n
when you raise it like this,

00:51:04.422 --> 00:51:07.010 align:middle line:84%
and then it should
give you that.

00:51:07.010 --> 00:51:09.410 align:middle line:84%
And just like with
the square root of 2,

00:51:09.410 --> 00:51:12.930 align:middle line:84%
there's just one element
with this property.

00:51:12.930 --> 00:51:15.710 align:middle line:90%
OK, So that's defined.

00:51:15.710 --> 00:51:21.810 align:middle line:84%
So you see this way we have
now defined this function, e,

00:51:21.810 --> 00:51:24.490 align:middle line:90%
on all rational numbers.

00:51:24.490 --> 00:51:26.710 align:middle line:90%
But now we need to check.

00:51:26.710 --> 00:51:29.010 align:middle line:84%
We need to check that--
this thing here--

00:51:29.010 --> 00:51:43.510 align:middle line:84%
we need to check that e
of q is equal like that.

00:51:43.510 --> 00:51:44.770 align:middle line:90%
So I need to check that.

00:51:44.770 --> 00:51:47.450 align:middle line:90%


00:51:47.450 --> 00:51:57.190 align:middle line:84%
So I want to say that e to
the q is that alpha, right?

00:51:57.190 --> 00:52:02.110 align:middle line:84%
So this means that
I want to show.

00:52:02.110 --> 00:52:08.710 align:middle line:84%
So I need to show two things,
e to q is positive-- well,

00:52:08.710 --> 00:52:10.510 align:middle line:90%
I've already checked that.

00:52:10.510 --> 00:52:14.130 align:middle line:84%
We checked that E, capital
E at anything is positive,

00:52:14.130 --> 00:52:15.750 align:middle line:90%
so this is OK.

00:52:15.750 --> 00:52:18.070 align:middle line:84%
The second thing
I need to check is

00:52:18.070 --> 00:52:25.710 align:middle line:84%
that it has the property that
if you raise it to the n power,

00:52:25.710 --> 00:52:33.110 align:middle line:84%
then you're getting
e to the m, right?

00:52:33.110 --> 00:52:36.730 align:middle line:84%
Now e to the m,
that's an integer.

00:52:36.730 --> 00:52:38.810 align:middle line:90%
It could be negative.

00:52:38.810 --> 00:52:42.360 align:middle line:84%
But e to any negative
integer, whether it's

00:52:42.360 --> 00:52:46.920 align:middle line:84%
positive or negative, we
already checked that this

00:52:46.920 --> 00:52:49.572 align:middle line:90%
is equal to capital e of m.

00:52:49.572 --> 00:52:53.120 align:middle line:90%


00:52:53.120 --> 00:52:56.580 align:middle line:90%
So now I need to show this here.

00:52:56.580 --> 00:52:57.740 align:middle line:90%
So now what is this?

00:52:57.740 --> 00:52:59.100 align:middle line:90%
So what do I need to check?

00:52:59.100 --> 00:53:09.920 align:middle line:84%
So I need to check
that e to the m over n,

00:53:09.920 --> 00:53:15.960 align:middle line:84%
this thing here, raised to
the power n is equal to this.

00:53:15.960 --> 00:53:18.040 align:middle line:90%
But what is this here?

00:53:18.040 --> 00:53:25.930 align:middle line:84%
This here is just e to the m
over n, multiply itself n times.

00:53:25.930 --> 00:53:29.520 align:middle line:90%


00:53:29.520 --> 00:53:31.070 align:middle line:90%
So this is now n times.

00:53:31.070 --> 00:53:34.920 align:middle line:90%


00:53:34.920 --> 00:53:39.700 align:middle line:84%
But now I can use, again, this
thing that I proved, next time,

00:53:39.700 --> 00:53:44.820 align:middle line:84%
that when I do it like here,
I'm just doing it 2 times,

00:53:44.820 --> 00:53:48.420 align:middle line:84%
and here I'm doing it
for different x and y.

00:53:48.420 --> 00:53:51.620 align:middle line:84%
But if I do it n
times with the same x,

00:53:51.620 --> 00:53:56.244 align:middle line:84%
then I'm just adding
that x together n times.

00:53:56.244 --> 00:53:59.620 align:middle line:90%


00:53:59.620 --> 00:54:03.900 align:middle line:84%
And so this thing
here is the same as e,

00:54:03.900 --> 00:54:09.340 align:middle line:84%
by that rule over
there, n times m over n.

00:54:09.340 --> 00:54:15.380 align:middle line:84%
But this is just E of
m, as it should be.

00:54:15.380 --> 00:54:18.460 align:middle line:84%
So you see that these
two functions here.

00:54:18.460 --> 00:54:32.150 align:middle line:84%
So the conclusion now is
that this function here

00:54:32.150 --> 00:54:42.730 align:middle line:84%
is equal to this function here
for all q for rational numbers.

00:54:42.730 --> 00:54:50.270 align:middle line:84%
Now, what other property should
this exponential-- so this here,

00:54:50.270 --> 00:54:52.310 align:middle line:84%
so far, this is
kind of the property

00:54:52.310 --> 00:54:54.490 align:middle line:84%
that you want of the
exponential function.

00:54:54.490 --> 00:54:58.910 align:middle line:84%
But what other properties should
the exponential function have?

00:54:58.910 --> 00:55:01.270 align:middle line:84%
You should have
one other property,

00:55:01.270 --> 00:55:03.590 align:middle line:84%
and that's enough
to determine it,

00:55:03.590 --> 00:55:05.610 align:middle line:84%
and that is it
should be continuous.

00:55:05.610 --> 00:55:11.430 align:middle line:84%
So one more property is that
this function e to the x,

00:55:11.430 --> 00:55:20.750 align:middle line:84%
when x is defined like
this, this function should

00:55:20.750 --> 00:55:27.110 align:middle line:84%
be continuous, and we'll
talk a little bit more

00:55:27.110 --> 00:55:31.460 align:middle line:84%
about continuous function
in just a second.

00:55:31.460 --> 00:55:39.050 align:middle line:84%
Now that I have a theorem that
we'll prove next time, one

00:55:39.050 --> 00:55:41.010 align:middle line:90%
of the next times.

00:55:41.010 --> 00:55:47.410 align:middle line:84%
And that is that, suppose
you take two functions,

00:55:47.410 --> 00:55:52.290 align:middle line:84%
so we then can appeal to
the following theorem.

00:55:52.290 --> 00:56:07.970 align:middle line:84%
If f and g are two
continuous functions

00:56:07.970 --> 00:56:21.930 align:middle line:90%
on r that agree on all of q.

00:56:21.930 --> 00:56:24.450 align:middle line:84%
So if you have two
continuous functions,

00:56:24.450 --> 00:56:27.910 align:middle line:84%
and if you restrict it
to the rational number,

00:56:27.910 --> 00:56:30.850 align:middle line:84%
then the two functions
are the same.

00:56:30.850 --> 00:56:32.810 align:middle line:84%
If they are both continuous,
then the function

00:56:32.810 --> 00:56:34.300 align:middle line:90%
has to be the same.

00:56:34.300 --> 00:56:40.580 align:middle line:84%
So this implies that f
is equal to g everywhere,

00:56:40.580 --> 00:56:42.690 align:middle line:84%
not just on the
rational function.

00:56:42.690 --> 00:56:43.710 align:middle line:90%
No, rational numbers.

00:56:43.710 --> 00:56:50.440 align:middle line:90%


00:56:50.440 --> 00:56:54.820 align:middle line:84%
So we prove that either next
time or the following time.

00:56:54.820 --> 00:56:59.260 align:middle line:84%
Let me just go
back and remind you

00:56:59.260 --> 00:57:02.180 align:middle line:84%
about what it means for a
function to be continuous.

00:57:02.180 --> 00:57:05.470 align:middle line:90%


00:57:05.470 --> 00:57:07.280 align:middle line:90%
So this is the following.

00:57:07.280 --> 00:57:18.340 align:middle line:90%


00:57:18.340 --> 00:57:19.600 align:middle line:90%
So continuous.

00:57:19.600 --> 00:57:25.460 align:middle line:90%


00:57:25.460 --> 00:57:31.460 align:middle line:84%
So suppose you take a
function, and the function,

00:57:31.460 --> 00:57:34.150 align:middle line:84%
it doesn't even need to
be defined on an interval.

00:57:34.150 --> 00:57:36.880 align:middle line:90%


00:57:36.880 --> 00:57:39.380 align:middle line:84%
But you may as well assume
that it's an interval,

00:57:39.380 --> 00:57:43.800 align:middle line:84%
but it doesn't need to be
defined on the interval.

00:57:43.800 --> 00:57:53.400 align:middle line:84%
So a function here,
f, is said to be

00:57:53.400 --> 00:58:04.240 align:middle line:84%
continuous at x here in the
domain where it's defined.

00:58:04.240 --> 00:58:13.320 align:middle line:84%
If for all epsilon
greater than 0,

00:58:13.320 --> 00:58:25.960 align:middle line:84%
there exists delta greater than
zero, such that if x minus x-0

00:58:25.960 --> 00:58:29.440 align:middle line:84%
is smaller than
delta, then the images

00:58:29.440 --> 00:58:31.590 align:middle line:90%
are epsilon close to each other.

00:58:31.590 --> 00:58:37.690 align:middle line:90%


00:58:37.690 --> 00:58:41.610 align:middle line:84%
And so again this
delta typically

00:58:41.610 --> 00:58:45.910 align:middle line:84%
depends not just on
epsilon, but also on x-0.

00:58:45.910 --> 00:58:50.010 align:middle line:90%


00:58:50.010 --> 00:58:55.210 align:middle line:84%
So it's continuous at a point
x-0 if this is the case,

00:58:55.210 --> 00:59:09.490 align:middle line:84%
and the function, f, here is
said to be continuous if it

00:59:09.490 --> 00:59:16.320 align:middle line:90%
is continuous at all points.

00:59:16.320 --> 00:59:25.535 align:middle line:90%


00:59:25.535 --> 00:59:32.950 align:middle line:84%
Now let's just look at
two simple examples,

00:59:32.950 --> 00:59:37.150 align:middle line:84%
and then once we
have those, then

00:59:37.150 --> 00:59:40.910 align:middle line:84%
together with some
algebraic rules that

00:59:40.910 --> 00:59:45.870 align:middle line:84%
are similar to the algebraic
rules that we had for sequences,

00:59:45.870 --> 00:59:51.670 align:middle line:84%
then we get a huge
number of examples.

00:59:51.670 --> 00:59:55.030 align:middle line:84%
We get a large
collection of examples

00:59:55.030 --> 00:59:57.670 align:middle line:90%
of continuous functions.

00:59:57.670 --> 01:00:00.390 align:middle line:84%
So the first example
is the simplest

01:00:00.390 --> 01:00:05.840 align:middle line:84%
of all examples, where f here
is the constant function.

01:00:05.840 --> 01:00:12.190 align:middle line:90%


01:00:12.190 --> 01:00:17.630 align:middle line:84%
So I'm thinking about f here
is defined from R into R.

01:00:17.630 --> 01:00:23.430 align:middle line:84%
And for each x in R, it's
equal to the same constant.

01:00:23.430 --> 01:00:25.590 align:middle line:90%
So that's f.

01:00:25.590 --> 01:00:29.240 align:middle line:84%
I want to show that this
f is a constant function,

01:00:29.240 --> 01:00:36.052 align:middle line:84%
is continuous, so
proof of continuity.

01:00:36.052 --> 01:00:46.560 align:middle line:90%


01:00:46.560 --> 01:00:52.960 align:middle line:84%
So given epsilon greater
than 0, at this point

01:00:52.960 --> 01:00:55.220 align:middle line:90%
you can pick any delta you want.

01:00:55.220 --> 01:00:56.640 align:middle line:90%
I'm just picking.

01:00:56.640 --> 01:01:00.920 align:middle line:84%
So let delta be
equal to 1, but you

01:01:00.920 --> 01:01:02.700 align:middle line:90%
could pick anything you want.

01:01:02.700 --> 01:01:06.960 align:middle line:84%
It has to be positive, but you
can pick anything you want.

01:01:06.960 --> 01:01:14.320 align:middle line:84%
Then you have that if x
minus x-0 is less than 1,

01:01:14.320 --> 01:01:20.600 align:middle line:84%
well then of course,
f of x minus f of x-0,

01:01:20.600 --> 01:01:23.280 align:middle line:90%
both of these numbers is c.

01:01:23.280 --> 01:01:28.540 align:middle line:84%
So the difference is c
minus c, so this is 0.

01:01:28.540 --> 01:01:32.180 align:middle line:84%
So this is surely
less than epsilon.

01:01:32.180 --> 01:01:36.400 align:middle line:84%
So this shows that the function
is continuous at all points.

01:01:36.400 --> 01:01:39.980 align:middle line:84%
And you see that you could
pick delta anything you want,

01:01:39.980 --> 01:01:44.360 align:middle line:84%
and, of course, in particular,
it doesn't even depend on x-0.

01:01:44.360 --> 01:01:47.470 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't depend on epsilon,
and it doesn't depend on x-0.

01:01:47.470 --> 01:01:50.120 align:middle line:90%


01:01:50.120 --> 01:01:55.100 align:middle line:84%
So the constant
functions are continuous.

01:01:55.100 --> 01:01:58.900 align:middle line:90%
What about the next symbol?

01:01:58.900 --> 01:02:04.340 align:middle line:84%
The next simplest function would
be the linear function, or just

01:02:04.340 --> 01:02:07.180 align:middle line:90%
x function, x.

01:02:07.180 --> 01:02:21.740 align:middle line:84%
So suppose you're looking
at the function f on R to R,

01:02:21.740 --> 01:02:25.910 align:middle line:90%
and where f of x is equal to x.

01:02:25.910 --> 01:02:27.890 align:middle line:90%
So this is also continuous.

01:02:27.890 --> 01:02:32.270 align:middle line:90%


01:02:32.270 --> 01:02:33.570 align:middle line:90%
Also continuous.

01:02:33.570 --> 01:02:37.310 align:middle line:90%


01:02:37.310 --> 01:02:42.200 align:middle line:84%
And the proof of
that, given epsilon.

01:02:42.200 --> 01:02:44.990 align:middle line:90%


01:02:44.990 --> 01:02:50.030 align:middle line:90%
set delta equal to epsilon.

01:02:50.030 --> 01:02:56.870 align:middle line:84%
Then you see that if x minus
x-0 is less than epsilon,

01:02:56.870 --> 01:03:05.590 align:middle line:84%
then f of x minus f of x-0,
but f of x is equal to x,

01:03:05.590 --> 01:03:08.550 align:middle line:90%
and f of x-0 is equal to x zero.

01:03:08.550 --> 01:03:13.000 align:middle line:84%
So this thing here is, of
course, less than epsilon,

01:03:13.000 --> 01:03:13.500 align:middle line:90%
right?

01:03:13.500 --> 01:03:17.630 align:middle line:90%


01:03:17.630 --> 01:03:20.710 align:middle line:90%
So that's kind of trivial.

01:03:20.710 --> 01:03:27.690 align:middle line:84%
Now the next thing is that we
have the algebraic property

01:03:27.690 --> 01:03:29.890 align:middle line:90%
of continuous functions.

01:03:29.890 --> 01:03:32.200 align:middle line:84%
So we have some
algebraic property.

01:03:32.200 --> 01:03:48.290 align:middle line:90%


01:03:48.290 --> 01:03:54.380 align:middle line:84%
Properties of
continuous function.

01:03:54.380 --> 01:04:00.130 align:middle line:90%


01:04:00.130 --> 01:04:03.490 align:middle line:84%
And I will prove a couple of
these, and the proofs you'll

01:04:03.490 --> 01:04:05.050 align:middle line:90%
see in just a second.

01:04:05.050 --> 01:04:09.650 align:middle line:90%


01:04:09.650 --> 01:04:11.190 align:middle line:84%
And there's good
reasons for that.

01:04:11.190 --> 01:04:13.290 align:middle line:84%
They're very similar
to the property

01:04:13.290 --> 01:04:17.490 align:middle line:84%
we had for limits of
sequences, and the proofs

01:04:17.490 --> 01:04:20.770 align:middle line:84%
are very similar
to those proofs.

01:04:20.770 --> 01:04:32.740 align:middle line:84%
So the first one is that
if f and g are continuous,

01:04:32.740 --> 01:04:36.680 align:middle line:84%
then the sum of these two
functions is also continuous.

01:04:36.680 --> 01:04:43.660 align:middle line:90%


01:04:43.660 --> 01:05:02.340 align:middle line:84%
The next one is that if f is
continuous and c is a constant,

01:05:02.340 --> 01:05:04.720 align:middle line:90%
then C times f is continuous.

01:05:04.720 --> 01:05:09.780 align:middle line:90%


01:05:09.780 --> 01:05:14.800 align:middle line:84%
The third property
is that, again,

01:05:14.800 --> 01:05:27.680 align:middle line:84%
if f comma g are
continuous, then the product

01:05:27.680 --> 01:05:29.580 align:middle line:90%
f times g is continuous.

01:05:29.580 --> 01:05:34.600 align:middle line:90%


01:05:34.600 --> 01:05:46.960 align:middle line:84%
The fourth property is
that if f is continuous,

01:05:46.960 --> 01:05:57.580 align:middle line:84%
and f is never equal to 0,
then one over f is continuous.

01:05:57.580 --> 01:06:02.480 align:middle line:90%


01:06:02.480 --> 01:06:05.660 align:middle line:84%
And the fifth property,
that's a little bit different.

01:06:05.660 --> 01:06:08.760 align:middle line:84%
We didn't have
that for sequences.

01:06:08.760 --> 01:06:13.520 align:middle line:84%
The fifth property is that
if you take a map, f of g,

01:06:13.520 --> 01:06:17.400 align:middle line:84%
take a function, f,
you think about it

01:06:17.400 --> 01:06:20.370 align:middle line:84%
as a function from
R to R, and then you

01:06:20.370 --> 01:06:25.970 align:middle line:84%
have another function,
g, from R to R.

01:06:25.970 --> 01:06:30.650 align:middle line:84%
And now you could look
at where you check first.

01:06:30.650 --> 01:06:33.250 align:middle line:84%
You could look at
the composition.

01:06:33.250 --> 01:06:35.570 align:middle line:84%
So you can look
at the function h

01:06:35.570 --> 01:06:41.450 align:middle line:84%
of x, which is where
you first apply f to x,

01:06:41.450 --> 01:06:45.150 align:middle line:90%
and then you apply g to it.

01:06:45.150 --> 01:06:53.370 align:middle line:84%
So if both f, so if this
here and the function g

01:06:53.370 --> 01:07:00.490 align:middle line:84%
are continuous,
then the composition

01:07:00.490 --> 01:07:02.150 align:middle line:90%
here is also continuous.

01:07:02.150 --> 01:07:07.930 align:middle line:90%


01:07:07.930 --> 01:07:09.930 align:middle line:84%
When you have a
composition of function,

01:07:09.930 --> 01:07:13.650 align:middle line:84%
you always have to be
careful that it makes sense.

01:07:13.650 --> 01:07:18.710 align:middle line:84%
So to make sense means that
the function, g, the one that--

01:07:18.710 --> 01:07:19.630 align:middle line:90%
this thing--

01:07:19.630 --> 01:07:23.950 align:middle line:84%
function that you apply,
is that the image of--

01:07:23.950 --> 01:07:25.830 align:middle line:84%
when you use the
first function, you

01:07:25.830 --> 01:07:29.950 align:middle line:84%
have to make sure
that what you get here

01:07:29.950 --> 01:07:34.590 align:middle line:84%
is at some point
where g is defined.

01:07:34.590 --> 01:07:40.710 align:middle line:84%
So just for simplicity, I just
looked at maps, into functions

01:07:40.710 --> 01:07:43.855 align:middle line:84%
into R where g also was
defined on all of that.

01:07:43.855 --> 01:07:45.730 align:middle line:84%
But of course, it doesn't
have to be defined,

01:07:45.730 --> 01:07:48.750 align:middle line:84%
but you just have to
make sure that g is

01:07:48.750 --> 01:07:51.650 align:middle line:90%
defined where f and x end up.

01:07:51.650 --> 01:07:54.610 align:middle line:90%


01:07:54.610 --> 01:07:59.990 align:middle line:84%
I'll talk a little bit
about how to prove these,

01:07:59.990 --> 01:08:03.310 align:middle line:84%
but it's very similar to
what we did for sequences.

01:08:03.310 --> 01:08:08.550 align:middle line:84%
Let me just apply it, so
let me look at an example

01:08:08.550 --> 01:08:09.970 align:middle line:90%
where I apply it.

01:08:09.970 --> 01:08:18.319 align:middle line:90%


01:08:18.319 --> 01:08:22.220 align:middle line:84%
So suppose you take
x squared plus 1.

01:08:22.220 --> 01:08:23.899 align:middle line:84%
Suppose you take
this function here.

01:08:23.899 --> 01:08:25.549 align:middle line:84%
I'll take a look
at two examples.

01:08:25.549 --> 01:08:29.399 align:middle line:90%


01:08:29.399 --> 01:08:32.520 align:middle line:84%
Suppose you take
this function here.

01:08:32.520 --> 01:08:35.680 align:middle line:84%
I claim that this
here is continuous.

01:08:35.680 --> 01:08:42.520 align:middle line:84%
I'm not going to go through
the proof because we already--

01:08:42.520 --> 01:08:47.359 align:middle line:84%
actually, so this here proves at
least some of these properties.

01:08:47.359 --> 01:08:54.720 align:middle line:84%
But once you have that, then
you have that g of x equal to x.

01:08:54.720 --> 01:08:57.120 align:middle line:90%
This here is continuous.

01:08:57.120 --> 01:09:02.279 align:middle line:84%
This is what we proved
just a little while ago.

01:09:02.279 --> 01:09:04.700 align:middle line:84%
And if you take the
function that is constant,

01:09:04.700 --> 01:09:07.920 align:middle line:84%
and in this case
constant 1, we already

01:09:07.920 --> 01:09:10.960 align:middle line:90%
proved that that's continuous.

01:09:10.960 --> 01:09:16.140 align:middle line:84%
Now this means that if you
take a continuous function

01:09:16.140 --> 01:09:20.660 align:middle line:84%
by whatever, rule three or
something like that over there,

01:09:20.660 --> 01:09:25.260 align:middle line:84%
and you take the function
where it's multiplied

01:09:25.260 --> 01:09:29.420 align:middle line:90%
by itself, this function here.

01:09:29.420 --> 01:09:31.740 align:middle line:90%
Because g is continuous.

01:09:31.740 --> 01:09:33.880 align:middle line:84%
This function here
is also continuous.

01:09:33.880 --> 01:09:39.819 align:middle line:90%


01:09:39.819 --> 01:09:48.779 align:middle line:84%
And then once you have that, you
can add it, g squared plus h.

01:09:48.779 --> 01:09:51.080 align:middle line:84%
You now have established
that this is continuous.

01:09:51.080 --> 01:09:53.140 align:middle line:84%
This is a constant
function, so we already

01:09:53.140 --> 01:09:54.720 align:middle line:90%
proved that this is continuous.

01:09:54.720 --> 01:09:58.440 align:middle line:84%
So the sum, by rule one over
there, this here is continuous.

01:09:58.440 --> 01:10:10.160 align:middle line:90%


01:10:10.160 --> 01:10:14.710 align:middle line:84%
So this show that this function
here, this quadratic function,

01:10:14.710 --> 01:10:15.870 align:middle line:90%
is continuous.

01:10:15.870 --> 01:10:17.870 align:middle line:84%
But in fact, of
course, this argument

01:10:17.870 --> 01:10:24.270 align:middle line:84%
gives you that any polynomial,
any polynomial is continuous.

01:10:24.270 --> 01:10:27.910 align:middle line:84%
So this here proves
that any polynomial--

01:10:27.910 --> 01:10:34.210 align:middle line:90%


01:10:34.210 --> 01:10:39.390 align:middle line:84%
So if you're using
1, 2, and 3 then

01:10:39.390 --> 01:10:42.110 align:middle line:84%
it's just starting at
the constant function.

01:10:42.110 --> 01:10:48.330 align:middle line:84%
And the function x, you
can get to any polynomial,

01:10:48.330 --> 01:10:50.410 align:middle line:90%
and using these operations.

01:10:50.410 --> 01:10:53.950 align:middle line:84%
And so this means that any
polynomial is continuous, right?

01:10:53.950 --> 01:11:02.090 align:middle line:84%
So you have the following
theorem, all polynomials.

01:11:02.090 --> 01:11:08.550 align:middle line:90%


01:11:08.550 --> 01:11:09.650 align:middle line:90%
are continuous.

01:11:09.650 --> 01:11:15.236 align:middle line:90%


01:11:15.236 --> 01:11:20.850 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, so this is just
using 1, 2, and 3 over here.

01:11:20.850 --> 01:11:26.610 align:middle line:84%
If you now also bring
in four, then you have--

01:11:26.610 --> 01:11:28.840 align:middle line:90%
so here is proof.

01:11:28.840 --> 01:11:32.330 align:middle line:90%


01:11:32.330 --> 01:11:36.530 align:middle line:84%
So it uses the two
examples that we gave,

01:11:36.530 --> 01:11:53.450 align:middle line:84%
and then in addition to that, it
follows from the algebraic rules

01:11:53.450 --> 01:11:56.890 align:middle line:90%
1 through 3.

01:11:56.890 --> 01:12:01.930 align:middle line:84%
If you bring in also 4, 5 is
something slightly different.

01:12:01.930 --> 01:12:06.210 align:middle line:84%
But if you bring
in 4 here, then you

01:12:06.210 --> 01:12:08.800 align:middle line:84%
get what's called any
rational function.

01:12:08.800 --> 01:12:15.140 align:middle line:90%


01:12:15.140 --> 01:12:16.680 align:middle line:90%
All rational functions.

01:12:16.680 --> 01:12:25.300 align:middle line:90%


01:12:25.300 --> 01:12:26.240 align:middle line:90%
are continuous.

01:12:26.240 --> 01:12:27.870 align:middle line:90%
So what is a rational function?

01:12:27.870 --> 01:12:32.500 align:middle line:90%


01:12:32.500 --> 01:12:34.300 align:middle line:84%
A rational function
is just where

01:12:34.300 --> 01:12:38.860 align:middle line:84%
you're taking a
polynomial, and then you're

01:12:38.860 --> 01:12:42.060 align:middle line:84%
dividing it by
another polynomial.

01:12:42.060 --> 01:12:45.500 align:middle line:84%
So we know that any
polynomial is continuous.

01:12:45.500 --> 01:12:47.500 align:middle line:90%
If you take another polynomial--

01:12:47.500 --> 01:12:53.080 align:middle line:84%
and let's look at that other
polynomial away from the roots,

01:12:53.080 --> 01:12:58.340 align:middle line:84%
away from where it is 0,
away from where it's 0.

01:12:58.340 --> 01:13:01.000 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it's of course even
continuous where it's 0,

01:13:01.000 --> 01:13:02.900 align:middle line:84%
but you can't
divide by it, right?

01:13:02.900 --> 01:13:10.600 align:middle line:84%
So away from it, this function
here is not 0 and is continuous.

01:13:10.600 --> 01:13:13.400 align:middle line:84%
This here is
continuous, rule four,

01:13:13.400 --> 01:13:28.260 align:middle line:84%
so this is proof that the
theorem above plus rule four.

01:13:28.260 --> 01:13:32.920 align:middle line:90%


01:13:32.920 --> 01:13:37.480 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Earlier you were
showing that the function of x

01:13:37.480 --> 01:13:41.240 align:middle line:84%
shows your delta as a
function of epsilon.

01:13:41.240 --> 01:13:42.240 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: Exactly.

01:13:42.240 --> 01:13:45.180 align:middle line:84%
In that case, I chose
delta to be simply epsilon.

01:13:45.180 --> 01:13:45.680 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:13:45.680 --> 01:13:46.790 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:13:46.790 --> 01:13:48.040 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: And you can do that?

01:13:48.040 --> 01:13:50.000 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING:
That's not a problem.

01:13:50.000 --> 01:13:54.160 align:middle line:84%
If you give me an epsilon,
then I have to pick a delta.

01:13:54.160 --> 01:13:58.160 align:middle line:84%
And typically, the delta
will depend on epsilon.

01:13:58.160 --> 01:14:01.560 align:middle line:84%
Typically, it also depends
on X. Let me give you

01:14:01.560 --> 01:14:04.080 align:middle line:90%
an example of the last.

01:14:04.080 --> 01:14:07.892 align:middle line:84%
I might not get to proving
this, but that's fine.

01:14:07.892 --> 01:14:09.350 align:middle line:84%
I mean, they're
actually the proof.

01:14:09.350 --> 01:14:12.990 align:middle line:84%
I'm not even sure I
would go through it.

01:14:12.990 --> 01:14:18.050 align:middle line:84%
Maybe if I have 10 minutes, I
will talk about one of them.

01:14:18.050 --> 01:14:19.650 align:middle line:90%
So let me give you an example.

01:14:19.650 --> 01:14:22.330 align:middle line:90%


01:14:22.330 --> 01:14:28.530 align:middle line:84%
So typically, it's highly
unusual in the first example

01:14:28.530 --> 01:14:31.790 align:middle line:84%
with a constant function that
it doesn't really matter.

01:14:31.790 --> 01:14:34.223 align:middle line:90%
You could pick delta anything.

01:14:34.223 --> 01:14:37.650 align:middle line:84%
Now suppose you're
looking at the function

01:14:37.650 --> 01:14:40.730 align:middle line:90%
f of x equal to 1 over x.

01:14:40.730 --> 01:14:44.510 align:middle line:84%
This is a rational function,
because it's a polynomial.

01:14:44.510 --> 01:14:46.930 align:middle line:84%
In that case, the polynomial
in the denominator

01:14:46.930 --> 01:14:54.290 align:middle line:84%
is the constant function, 1,
and then the denominator is x.

01:14:54.290 --> 01:14:59.530 align:middle line:84%
Let's just look at this function
where it's strictly positive.

01:14:59.530 --> 01:15:05.070 align:middle line:84%
And then you see now the graph
looks basically like this.

01:15:05.070 --> 01:15:08.610 align:middle line:84%
So in particular, if
you go close to 0--

01:15:08.610 --> 01:15:09.650 align:middle line:90%
it's not defined as 0.

01:15:09.650 --> 01:15:15.190 align:middle line:84%
But if you go close to 0,
then the image varies a lot.

01:15:15.190 --> 01:15:21.850 align:middle line:84%
So if you take some
fixed thing here,

01:15:21.850 --> 01:15:28.430 align:middle line:84%
suppose you want to prove that
it's continuous at some x zero.

01:15:28.430 --> 01:15:31.870 align:middle line:84%
So this means that you
have to pick some delta.

01:15:31.870 --> 01:15:35.230 align:middle line:84%
So given an epsilon,
you have to pick a delta

01:15:35.230 --> 01:15:39.030 align:middle line:84%
so that if you are in
this little interval,

01:15:39.030 --> 01:15:41.570 align:middle line:84%
then the image lies in
that little interval.

01:15:41.570 --> 01:15:45.790 align:middle line:84%
But you see that as x-0
becomes very close to 0,

01:15:45.790 --> 01:15:50.870 align:middle line:84%
then in any small interval,
the function varies a lot.

01:15:50.870 --> 01:15:57.650 align:middle line:84%
So this means that if you
take some fixed epsilon,

01:15:57.650 --> 01:16:01.950 align:middle line:84%
then you expect that if
the x-0 was close to 0,

01:16:01.950 --> 01:16:04.100 align:middle line:84%
then the delta had
to be really, really,

01:16:04.100 --> 01:16:08.000 align:middle line:90%
really small for this to work.

01:16:08.000 --> 01:16:12.940 align:middle line:84%
So typically, delta depends
not just on epsilon--

01:16:12.940 --> 01:16:16.320 align:middle line:84%
which, I mean, it's highly
unusual it doesn't--

01:16:16.320 --> 01:16:17.860 align:middle line:90%
it also depends on x.

01:16:17.860 --> 01:16:21.440 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, if it doesn't
depend on x or x-0,

01:16:21.440 --> 01:16:23.260 align:middle line:90%
then it has a particular name.

01:16:23.260 --> 01:16:24.340 align:middle line:90%
We'll get to that later.

01:16:24.340 --> 01:16:26.360 align:middle line:90%
It's called uniform continuity.

01:16:26.360 --> 01:16:30.420 align:middle line:84%
Uniform continuity has
some nice extra properties.

01:16:30.420 --> 01:16:33.560 align:middle line:90%


01:16:33.560 --> 01:16:36.120 align:middle line:84%
And you will see
later on that there's

01:16:36.120 --> 01:16:42.160 align:middle line:84%
a good reason why the domain
here did not include 0.

01:16:42.160 --> 01:16:46.360 align:middle line:84%
If somehow this would have been
a continuous function defined

01:16:46.360 --> 01:16:50.200 align:middle line:84%
on an interval that included
the end point, then actually

01:16:50.200 --> 01:16:52.460 align:middle line:84%
it would automatically
be uniform continuous.

01:16:52.460 --> 01:16:55.140 align:middle line:90%
So it was a good reason.

01:16:55.140 --> 01:17:03.500 align:middle line:84%
This example here, it
didn't include the point 0.

01:17:03.500 --> 01:17:05.720 align:middle line:90%
So I have three minutes left.

01:17:05.720 --> 01:17:10.120 align:middle line:84%
Let me just talk about
one particular of these.

01:17:10.120 --> 01:17:13.820 align:middle line:84%
Like, the first one and the
second one is super easy,

01:17:13.820 --> 01:17:16.240 align:middle line:90%
and the third one is also easy.

01:17:16.240 --> 01:17:18.460 align:middle line:84%
And it uses exactly
the same trick

01:17:18.460 --> 01:17:20.380 align:middle line:84%
that we looked at
before, so let me just

01:17:20.380 --> 01:17:22.720 align:middle line:90%
talk about that for a minute.

01:17:22.720 --> 01:17:27.460 align:middle line:84%
Just because it's a little bit
more interesting than 1 and 2,

01:17:27.460 --> 01:17:28.980 align:middle line:90%
is barely interesting.

01:17:28.980 --> 01:17:34.620 align:middle line:84%
So suppose I'm looking at the
product of these two functions.

01:17:34.620 --> 01:17:37.660 align:middle line:84%
And so remember that
you give me an epsilon,

01:17:37.660 --> 01:17:39.480 align:middle line:90%
I have to find a delta.

01:17:39.480 --> 01:17:44.500 align:middle line:84%
So I have to find a delta
so that this difference here

01:17:44.500 --> 01:17:46.820 align:middle line:90%
is smaller.

01:17:46.820 --> 01:17:53.540 align:middle line:84%
I want to find the delta, so
that if x minus x-0 is smaller,

01:17:53.540 --> 01:17:56.300 align:middle line:84%
if it's smaller than delta,
then this difference here

01:17:56.300 --> 01:17:57.960 align:middle line:90%
is smaller than epsilon, right?

01:17:57.960 --> 01:18:02.150 align:middle line:84%
That's what I'm supposed
to do to just knowing

01:18:02.150 --> 01:18:05.310 align:middle line:90%
that f and g are continuous.

01:18:05.310 --> 01:18:10.750 align:middle line:84%
And so just like when we
had this for sequences,

01:18:10.750 --> 01:18:14.790 align:middle line:84%
the similar thing
for sequences, it's

01:18:14.790 --> 01:18:18.030 align:middle line:84%
too complicated if you
just look at it like this.

01:18:18.030 --> 01:18:22.410 align:middle line:84%
So what you do is that you
take f of x times g of x.

01:18:22.410 --> 01:18:26.310 align:middle line:84%
You insert something,
and it doesn't really

01:18:26.310 --> 01:18:32.110 align:middle line:84%
matter which way you do it, but
this is halfway between this

01:18:32.110 --> 01:18:35.690 align:middle line:84%
and that where you take
one point to be x-0,

01:18:35.690 --> 01:18:36.790 align:middle line:90%
the others are x.

01:18:36.790 --> 01:18:41.790 align:middle line:84%
Of course, you didn't have that,
so you have to add it again.

01:18:41.790 --> 01:18:44.510 align:middle line:84%
But now the thing is that
what you've done here

01:18:44.510 --> 01:18:47.130 align:middle line:84%
is you have split the
difference, if you will.

01:18:47.130 --> 01:18:50.150 align:middle line:90%


01:18:50.150 --> 01:18:54.670 align:middle line:84%
And so now when you
want to estimate this,

01:18:54.670 --> 01:18:56.810 align:middle line:84%
you estimate this
thing here first.

01:18:56.810 --> 01:19:05.250 align:middle line:84%
So this is g of x times
f of x minus f of x-0.

01:19:05.250 --> 01:19:09.930 align:middle line:84%
And you take the
absolute value of this,

01:19:09.930 --> 01:19:18.690 align:middle line:84%
and then here you can
factor out f of x-0 and g

01:19:18.690 --> 01:19:23.190 align:middle line:90%
of x minus g of x here.

01:19:23.190 --> 01:19:26.090 align:middle line:84%
Now, you can do
like we did before.

01:19:26.090 --> 01:19:30.890 align:middle line:84%
This here is now fixed, so you
can also take the absolute value

01:19:30.890 --> 01:19:34.170 align:middle line:90%
sign like that.

01:19:34.170 --> 01:19:38.790 align:middle line:84%
And now x-0 is fixed, so this
is just some fixed number.

01:19:38.790 --> 01:19:40.650 align:middle line:84%
So this means that
this thing here

01:19:40.650 --> 01:19:43.410 align:middle line:84%
has to be maybe even
smaller, depending

01:19:43.410 --> 01:19:44.830 align:middle line:90%
on what this constant is.

01:19:44.830 --> 01:19:48.370 align:middle line:84%
But that's easy to achieve
with some delta, right?

01:19:48.370 --> 01:19:50.690 align:middle line:84%
Here, it's a little
bit more complicated

01:19:50.690 --> 01:19:53.440 align:middle line:84%
because this one
here is not fixed.

01:19:53.440 --> 01:19:59.260 align:middle line:84%
But you have to then say that
once you are close to x-0,

01:19:59.260 --> 01:20:02.500 align:middle line:84%
then this here is
bound for this.

01:20:02.500 --> 01:20:05.180 align:middle line:84%
You see, it's like
what we did before.

01:20:05.180 --> 01:20:09.340 align:middle line:84%
So we're out of time, so
I'll just leave it there.

01:20:09.340 --> 01:20:11.460 align:middle line:84%
So next time we'll
talk more about this

01:20:11.460 --> 01:20:12.640 align:middle line:90%
with exponential function.

01:20:12.640 --> 01:20:13.260 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

01:20:13.260 --> 01:20:14.677 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So our
rational function

01:20:14.677 --> 01:20:17.940 align:middle line:84%
is said to be continuous or do
we not call them continuous?

01:20:17.940 --> 01:20:19.120 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: No.

01:20:19.120 --> 01:20:21.540 align:middle line:84%
Any rational function
is continuous.

01:20:21.540 --> 01:20:29.780 align:middle line:84%
It's defined at points where the
polynomial in the denominator

01:20:29.780 --> 01:20:35.806 align:middle line:84%
away from the roots of the
polynomial in the denominator.

01:20:35.806 --> 01:20:37.000 align:middle line:90%
It's continuous.

01:20:37.000 --> 01:20:37.700 align:middle line:90%
What?

01:20:37.700 --> 01:20:39.140 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: It's said to be
non-continuous if the roots

01:20:39.140 --> 01:20:40.585 align:middle line:90%
of the polynomial [INAUDIBLE]?

01:20:40.585 --> 01:20:41.460 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: What?

01:20:41.460 --> 01:20:44.020 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, I mean, any rational
function is continuous.

01:20:44.020 --> 01:20:47.820 align:middle line:84%
It's just not
defined at the roots.

01:20:47.820 --> 01:20:53.000 align:middle line:84%
OK, now for some polynomial,
some rational functions,

01:20:53.000 --> 01:21:00.820 align:middle line:84%
if you were silly and you
wrote this thing here,

01:21:00.820 --> 01:21:02.460 align:middle line:90%
this is a polynomial.

01:21:02.460 --> 01:21:03.540 align:middle line:90%
That's a polynomial.

01:21:03.540 --> 01:21:07.560 align:middle line:84%
This one has a root at 0, but
really, this function here, you

01:21:07.560 --> 01:21:13.340 align:middle line:84%
would probably think about as
being the constant function 1.

01:21:13.340 --> 01:21:14.760 align:middle line:90%
But it's not a pure--

01:21:14.760 --> 01:21:19.540 align:middle line:84%
it's continuous
away from the root.

01:21:19.540 --> 01:21:22.340 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't say whether it's
continuous at the root.

01:21:22.340 --> 01:21:27.200 align:middle line:84%
It's just not defined at
the root of the denominator.

01:21:27.200 --> 01:21:28.400 align:middle line:90%
Yep.

01:21:28.400 --> 01:21:30.440 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: [? One ?]
point is not like that.

01:21:30.440 --> 01:21:32.260 align:middle line:84%
You didn't say continuous
or [INAUDIBLE].

01:21:32.260 --> 01:21:32.840 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: Yep.

01:21:32.840 --> 01:21:33.420 align:middle line:90%
That's right.

01:21:33.420 --> 01:21:34.238 align:middle line:90%
That's right.

01:21:34.238 --> 01:21:34.780 align:middle line:90%
That's right.

01:21:34.780 --> 01:21:38.080 align:middle line:84%
So if you have a polynomial
in the denominator,

01:21:38.080 --> 01:21:42.440 align:middle line:84%
there's finitely many
points where you have roots.

01:21:42.440 --> 01:21:45.300 align:middle line:84%
And at those points, it's
absolutely not defined.

01:21:45.300 --> 01:21:48.240 align:middle line:84%
You might be able to extend
it in a continuous way

01:21:48.240 --> 01:21:49.500 align:middle line:90%
to those points.

01:21:49.500 --> 01:21:52.950 align:middle line:84%
But typically, it's not
defined in those points.

01:21:52.950 --> 01:21:56.000 align:middle line:90%